<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Summoning the ghosts of war dead and the judgment of
history, House prosecutors wrapped up their opening presentation
at President Clinton's impeachment trial Saturday with a call to
restore the "sacred honor" of the presidency lest it become
"deeply and perhaps permanently damaged."
</P>
<P>
-- At least 45 ethnic Albanians were found killed Saturday in
the village of Racak in the breakaway Serbian province of Kosovo
in what appeared to be the bloodiest spree in the year-long
conflict between the warring sides.
</P>
<P>
-- The CIA told President Clinton in a highly classified
report last month that material released into the atmosphere
during an underground nuclear test by Pakistan the previous May
contained low levels of weapons-grade plutonium, according to
U.S. national security officials.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Brazil's Finance Minister began talks in Washington Satur
day with the international Monetary Fund and said he might ask
for early release of the next round of international assistance
to the country to help stabilize its economy.
</P>
<P>
-- With tensions rising on the Korean peninsula, the United
States and North Korea opened new talks in Geneva on whether
North Korea will allow inspections of a suspected underground
nuclear installation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
