<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Issue Tops Arab Ministerial Meeting: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said here on Sunday that the Iraqi issue will top the
agenda of an Arab foreign ministers conference slated for January
24.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with the Cairo-based Arab League chief Esmat
Abdel-Meguid, Moussa told reporters that Arab countries will
continue intensive consultations Saturday to ensure success for
the conference.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries had originally planned to hold the conference on
December 30 to discuss the Iraqi crisis following the U.S.-British
air strikes on Iraq on December 16-19.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain launched the strikes for what
they said the Iraqi failure to fully cooperate with the
U.N. weapons inspectors in charge of disarming Iraq of weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Given the differences among the Gulf Arab states, the Arab
League announced a postponement of the conference on December
28. Arab officials have since been engaging in intensive
consultations and preparations.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said he briefed Abdel-Meguid on the outcome of the
recent consultations to set the scene for the conference.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of Egypt, Oman, Saudi Arabia, Syria and
Yemen met on January 2 and 13 and discussed the agenda of the
conference.
</P>
<P>
"We are preparing through coordination and calm dialog in order
to serve the Arab interests and grapple with the formidable
problems in the region," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said the current coordination and consultations
are aimed at ensuring success for the Arab foreign ministers'
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will have a "difficult" task, but they will try
to reach a clear Arab position regarding the Iraqi issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid expressed belief that military means "did not and
will not solve the problem regarding Iraq," saying the U.S. and
Britain "do not achieve anything with their use of power."
</P>
<P>
The Arab League, a pan-Arab organization, is "serious" in
seeking ways of getting the economic sanctions, imposed on Iraq
following its invasion of Kuwait, lifted to end the sufferings of
the Iraqi people, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
