<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni Kicks off Visit to Namibia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni left for a short working visit to Namibia Sunday at the
invitation of Namibian President Sam Nujoma.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued Sunday evening by the President's
Office said that the two heads of state will discuss bilateral
issues as well as issues concerning the region.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that the two leaders will hold talks on
the situation in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and other
regional matters.
</P>
<P>
Museveni, accompanied by State Minister of Regional Cooperation
Amama Mbabazi, was seen off at Entebbe International Airport, 45
kilometers south of Kampala, by First Lady Janet Museveni,
Vice-President Specioza Kazibwe and other senior officials.
</P>
<P>
Museveni made the trip following the announcement of
postponement of the Lusaka summit.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka summit, originally scheduled for this weekend, was
reportedly put off again because DRC President Laurent Kabila
still refused to talk directly with the Tutsi rebels anywhere
outside Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, supported by forces from Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia and
Chad, has refused to hold face-to-face talks with the rebels
fighting to oust him. With rebels now occupying about 45 percent
land in the third largest African country, the situation there is
becoming increasingly volatile and unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
Both regional and international efforts aimed at bring a
military standstill in the country have failed with neither side
agreeing to concede. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Denounces Iraqi Provocation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait Sunday condemned
Iraq's non-recognition of the U.N.-demarcated Iraqi-Kuwaiti
border and denied its accusation over the U.S.-British air strikes
on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued after a weekly cabinet session said "the
cabinet reasserts its rejection and condemnation of these Iraqi
measures and statements which reflect negligence of international
resolutions," the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The moves also constituted provocation against the oil-rich
Gulf emirate, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
On January 9, some Iraqi lawmakers urged scrapping U.N.
resolution 833, which demarcates the Iraqi-Kuwaiti border in 1993,
two years after the 1991 Gulf War, set off by Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Last Sunday, Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf
held Kuwait and Saudi Arabia accountable for Iraq's human and
property losses in the U.S.-British air strikes on December 16-19
because they allowed the two countries to use their airspace and
bases for the bombardment.
</P>
<P>
This is the first response from Kuwaiti government ever since.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Kuwaiti cabinet praised other member states of
the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) for their support to Kuwait
and their calls on Iraq to abide by international resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic organization
established in 1981, comprises Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar,
Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saddam Chairs Meeting on Proposals on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
on Sunday chaired a meeting of senior officials to discuss draft
proposals now on the Security Council table regarding the embargo
imposed on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, an official spokesman said any practical and
fair solution that will keep the region and the world away from
crises and repeated aggressive acts should keep off the
double-standard policy, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
France, the U.S. and Russia proposed plans this week to the
U.N. Security Counil to settle the Iraqi issue.
</P>
<P>
In their plans, France and Russia recommended oil embargo on
Iraq should be lifted and the U.N. Special Commission on disarming
Iraq (UNSCOM) be replaced by a new arms control commission.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. proposed in its plan to allow Iraq to sell as
much oil as it wants, and to keep UNSCOM in place and continue its
mission.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman did not reveal the details of the meeting,
but reiterated the same measures and arrangements imposed on
Iraq should be adopted against Israel.
</P>
<P>
The embargo imposed on Iraq since 1990 following Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait should be lifted totally and immediately, said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said what was done concerning Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction was enough and Iraq had fulfilled all its
obligations, adding Israel's weapons of mass destruction should be
dismantled.
</P>
<P>
The matter of reparations Iraq has deserved due to the
aggression since 1991 should be tackled according to the
international law, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Other parties concerned should bear the costs of any
U.N. activity as it was unfair and unacceptable that Iraq born the
costs, he added.
</P>
<P>
The meeting reiterated that Iraq's sovereignty, security and
independence should be seriously respected, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting asserted Iraq's determination to protect
its air spaces from the U.S.-British warplanes's violation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and its Western allies imposed no-fly zones in
northern and southern Iraq after the 1991 Gulf War. Baghdad
denounced them as unauthorized by the U.N. and illegal.
</P>
<P>
Present at the meeting were Vice-Chairman of the
Revolutionary Command Council (RCC) Izzat Ibrahim, Vice-President
Taha Yassin Ramadhan, Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz, RCC
member Ali Hassan as-Majeed, Speaker of the National Assembly
Sadoun Hammadi and Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0013 </DOCNO>
