<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Begins Inquiry Into Alleged Legal Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 17 (Xinhua) - Israel's police opened an
intensive investigation Sunday into an alleged legal scandal
which has rocked the law enforcement and political establishment
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The National Fraud Squad of the police summoned two key
figures in the affair for questioning, trying to find out who
is behind a series of forged documents which charged that a
drug case 17 years ago was a judicial scandal, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Yehiam Ohana, a business man living in the north who was
sentenced to two-and-half years in prison in 1982 on conviction
of drug dealings and has been requesting a retrial for the case
over recent years, was questioned by the police for the whole day,
the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Rachael Lev, who was hired by Ohana to help in his request for
retrial and suspected of forging documents trying to prove his
innocence, was brought to the investigators by the police after
she failed to appear before them citing a nerve breakdown.
</P>
<P>
The case burst into the limelight last week after the local
newspaper Ma'ariv reported that the country's Attorney-General
Elyakim Rubinstein was studying some documents he received
recently which alleged that Ohana was framed 17 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The documents claimed that police officers fabricated the
drug dealing charges against Ohana in an attempt to prevent
one of his close friend from being appointed police chief in
the northern areas.
</P>
<P>
They said the police officers blackmailed the presiding judge
into convicting Ohana, threatening to make public information in
their obsession that the judge raped a young woman and then
sent her to the United States to keep her silent.
</P>
<P>
Involving many people in the law enforcement systems, some
of them holding senior positions nowadays, the reported legal
scandal sent a shock wave around the country.
</P>
<P>
But the whole story soon turned out to be a different
legal scandal. The police and state prosecutor's office said
some of the documents presented to Rubinstein were forged.
</P>
<P>
Hanan Porat, chairman of the parliament's law committee, who
originally received the documents and passed them on to
Rubinstein earlier this month, has said that it is hard for
him to believe that all the documents are forged.
</P>
<P>
He added that he found it "inappropriate" that the police were
conducting the investigation in the affair.
</P>
<P>
"The documents contain very serious allegations regarding the
most senior police officers. Therefore the police is not an
objective body in this case," he said.
</P>
<P>
He and another legislator Doron Shmueli, a close friend of
Ohana, are expected to be questioned about the source of the
documents. The Ma'ariv reporter who first revealed the case is
also expected to be summoned for questioning.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Ohana denied rumors that he had fallen victim to a
fraud scheme made up by Lev, saying Lev had refused to take money
from him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Frees Militants Before Muslim Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) released 34 militant group members Sunday in honor
of the Eid al-Fitr Monday, the end of the holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
The freed are the members of the Islamic Resistance Movement
(Hamas) and Islamic Jihad. Some of them have been held for a year
without trial, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
In response, a spokesman of Hamas said on Sunday that the
PNA's gesture was "insufficient" and some Hamas leaders are still
in jail.
</P>
<P>
Hamas spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin has also complained
that the current security cooperation between the PNA, Israel and
the U.S. was blocking the Hamas attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
In early December, Israel suspended the implementation of the
Wye River peace agreement signed with the PNA last October.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Israel withdraws its troops from another
13 percent of the West Bank in exchange for the PNA's tougher
action on Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
Despite the suspension of the peace deal, negotiations between
the two sides are still underway over the security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said Saturday that
he has held meetings with officials of the Palestinian security
services over the past two weeks in a bid to strengthen the
security cooperation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of the Israeli general elections in May, it is reported
that the PNA does not hope to have terrorist attacks take place
lest they are capitalized on by the right-wing candidates in the
race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
