<HEADLINE> 4th Round of Burundi Peace Talks to Start Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The fourth round of
Burundi peace talks will open Monday amid hopes that economic
sanctions on the tiny central African nation could be lifted,
according to reports reaching here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
All factions in Burundi, as well as two former presidents of
the country, Sylvestre Ntibantunganya and Jean Baptiste Bagaza,
are expected to attend the talks in Arusha, north Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
This round of talks will debate on the reconstruction and
development of Burundi, Mark Bomani, an aide to the peace mediator
Julius Nyerere, was quoted as saying Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The past three rounds, also under the chairmanship of Nyerere,
former president of Tanzania and a veteran African statesman, have
debated on the nature of Burundi conflict, democracy and good
governance, and peace and security for all.
</P>
<P>
The talks have been trying to end a bitter ethnic conflict in
which more than 150,000 people, mostly civilians, have been killed
in the past few years in a series of massacres and in armed
conflicts between the Tutsi-dominated army and Hutu rebels.
</P>
<P>
The new round of talks starts ahead of a scheduled meeting of
the heads of Great Lakes states next Saturday to review progress
attained at the talks and discuss the possibility of fully or
partially suspending economic sanctions imposed on Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Major Pierre Buyoya came to power in a military coup in July of
1996, toppling a civilian government led by Ntibantunganya. East
and central African countries, backed by the Organization of
African Unity (OAU), imposed sanctions on Burundi shortly after
the incident.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
