<HEADLINE> Iran Condemns Massacre of Albanians in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry Sunday
condemned the recent massacre of Albanian Muslims in Kosovo after
an international observer mission reported mass execution in the
Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi expressed regret
over the killings over the past two days, the Islamic Republic
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that at least 45 ethnic Albanians were killed, and
their bodies were found at Racak, near Stimlje town, 30 kilometers
south of Pristina, by the Kosovo Verification Mission of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The tensions in Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia, have
heightened since February 1998 when bloody clashes erupted between
Serbian police and ethnic Albanians who demand independence from
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Asefi voiced concern over the repetition of such tragic events
in Kosovo, saying the Muslim world is concerned about the ongoing
situation in Kosovo and the hardship imposed on Muslims there.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, he said, certain countries' political abuse has
deteriorated the situation in Kosovo, causing further loss of
lives, destruction of houses and displacement of many people in
the cold winter.
</P>
<P>
But he did not specify the countries by name.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Republic of Iran, as the chairman of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference, urges immediate halt to
the killings, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Those responsible for such a heinous crimes should be brought
to justice, he added. 
</P>
