<HEADLINE> UK Highest Court to Rehear Pinochet's Immunity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Seven of Britain's most senior
judges will begin on Monday to rehear former Chilean leader
Augusto Pinochet's claim that he is immune from prosecution and
extradition outside Chile.
</P>
<P>
If they find in favor of the retired general, he will be
whisked to a military airfield where a Chilean Air Force plane is
on standby to fly him back to Santiago, the capital city of Chile.
</P>
<P>
But if they rule against him, a series of appeals will follow
on for many months to come.
</P>
<P>
Monday's rehearing is the latest step in a lengthy and complex
legal process.
</P>
<P>
Last November, five judges of the House of Lords, Britain's
highest court, ruled by three to two that Pinochet had no immunity
from immunity as a former head of state.
</P>
<P>
Their decision made possible the proceedings to extradite him
to face trial in Spain, where a judge has claimed that Pinochet is
responsible for the deaths and disappearances of 3,000 people
during his 17 year rule in Chile, which ended in 1990.
</P>
<P>
However in December, the House of Lords set aside its own rule
in the previous month, in an unprecedented move which deeply
embarrassed British government law officers.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet's lawyers had protested that one member of the
November panel had failed to declare his close links with Amnesty
International, the human right body which strongly support the
charges against Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Amnesty International and the Chilean
government are permitted to intervene in the rehearings on Monday,
which will take place before a new seven-judge panel.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet was arrested on October 16 in a London hospital while
recovering from a back operation after receiving the Spanish
extradition request. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
