<HEADLINE> Primakov: Yeltsin Hospitalization No Threat to Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov said Sunday that President Boris Yeltsin felt fine and
that his latest confinement to hospital did not threaten the
stability of Russia.
</P>
<P>
"The president feels fine," Primakov told the Itar-Tass news
agency after Yeltsin was taken to the Central Clinical Hospital
with a bleeding stomach ulcer.
</P>
<P>
"No extraordinary situation has arisen in the country due to
the president's illness," Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference Sunday evening, presidential spokesman
Dmitry Yakushkin said that Yeltsin fully preserves his power.
</P>
<P>
"No special decisions or special instructions followed the
hospitalization of the president," Tass quoted Yakushkin as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said a planned trip to France on January 28-29 would be
decided by Yeltsin and French President Jacques Chirac. There were
reports saying that Yeltsin could stay in hospital for as long as
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
Primakov has been in day-to-day charge of affairs since Yeltsin
appointed him prime minister last September following the
financial crisis in August which brought about the fall of the
previous government.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he was in permanent contact with
Yeltsin and there was no more to the president's illness than the
Kremlin had already announced.
</P>
<P>
Yakushkin, the presidential spokesman, told reporters that he
talked to Yeltsin Sunday afternoon and Yeltsin's voice "is rather
cheerful."
</P>
<P>
"Naturally, the president is upset by some changes in his
schedule which has been drafted for next week," Yakushkin said.
"He is upset as every person who suddenly gets sick. In fact,
nobody likes to start the new year at hospital."
</P>
<P>
This was the second time that Yeltsin was hospitalized since
early last December when he was admitted into the same hospital
for pneumonia, after only three hours in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, 67, planned to return to the Kremlin last Thursday
after the New Year holiday, but canceled his arrangements without
explanation. 
</P>
