<HEADLINE> EU, Polish Ambassadors Return to Minsk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The ambassadors of Britain,
France, Germany, Greece and Poland returned to Minsk Sunday, about
a nearly seven-month absence from the Belarussian capital.
</P>
<P>
The return marks a partial end to a row between Minsk and
Western missions over the diplomatic missions in the Drozdy
compound, site of the residence of Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador of the United States remains at home for
"consultations". It is also not clear whether or when the Japanese
ambassador will return to Minsk.
</P>
<P>
The heads of the EU diplomatic missions, including candidate
countries to the EU, as well as the U.S. and Japan were recalled
last June "for an indefinite period of consultations" due to the
conflict over Drozdy.
</P>
<P>
Last April, the Belarussian Foreign Ministry advised that
ambassadors in Drozdy move out of the compound to other places in
Minsk or in the capital's suburbs as the compound needed
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
Many ambassadors described their eviction from Drozdy as a
violation of the convention on diplomatic missions.
</P>
<P>
Following the ambassadors' departure, some Western countries
imposed a ban on entry visas to most Belarussian leaders.
</P>
<P>
With the return of the diplomats, the ban would be lifted
within weeks, Itar-Tass quoted British Ambassador Jessica Pearce
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Talks on settling the Drozdy row started several months ago and
a compromise was reached last December.
</P>
<P>
"Bygone is bygone," French Ambassador Bernard Fassier said at
the Minsk airport. "We should concentrate now and create effective
cooperation between our countries."
</P>
<P>
According to their December compromise, ambassadors will have
access to Drozdy for a month after their return. They have to move
their residences from Drozdy to other places within the period,
Tass said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
