<HEADLINE> Zambian Bank Warns Against Fake Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Zambia has warned
the public against carrying out foreign exchange transactions on
the streets in view of increased incidences of counterfeit U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
A bank spokesman warned Sunday that the fake 10-thousand-Kwacha
 (one Dollar equals over 2,000 Kwacha) notes that were in
circulation in the Copper Belt have spread to capital Lusaka,
reported the Zambia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said that a large amount had been found with a person of
foreign origin by police, who is now helping with the
investigations.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said many people had been swindled out of
thousands of genuine U.S. Dollars by street dealers who trick them
into exchanging Dollars with counterfeit notes.
</P>
<P>
It appears that the fake Dollars are thriving on the market
going by the amounts being detected and also the amounts being
used to swindle people out of their genuine Dollar notes, he said.
</P>
<P>
He warned shop owners, especially those running night clubs
and bars to be especially careful when transacting in the
10-thousand-Kwacha notes. 
