<HEADLINE> Iraq Raps U.S. Illegal Access to Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraq Sunday condemned the
illegal access of a U.S. delegation to northern Iraq via Turkey to
meet leaders of Kurdish warring factions.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed foreign ministry spokesman said a U.S. delegation
led by Elizabeth Joans, the State Department undersecretary
assistant, has entered northern Iraq illegally with a number of
Turkish foreign ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
But he did not say when the delegation entered northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation met leaders of Kurdish warring factions to
discuss schemes against the Iraqi people, the Iraqi News Agency
quoted the spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
The real aim of the Americans is to maintain the status quo of
the Kurdish autonomous region, he added.
</P>
<P>
After the 1991 Gulf War triggered by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait
in 1990, the U.S-led western allies set up a no-fly zone in
northern Iraq with a claimed aim of keeping minority Kurds from
Baghdad's oppression. Baghdad has since lost its control over the
region.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Turkey Kurdistan Democratic Party and the Patriotic
Union of Kurdistan in northern Iraq signed a peace deal in
September 1998 after seven years of fighting for the control over
the region.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said it has become very clear that foreign
interferences coming from Turkish territories have complicated the
situation in northern Iraq and pushed it toward a tragic direction
that threatened the life and security of the Kurdish people.
</P>
<P>
He called for an immediate end to these interferences in
Iraq's internal affairs so that the Iraqi central government's
authority will be re-established in the region and prosperity of
Iraqi people can be achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
