<HEADLINE> Egypt, Jordan, Palestinians to Discuss Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said here Sunday that he and his Jordanian and Palestinian
counterparts have planned to hold a meeting on the stalled
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters that the three ministers will meet in
Jordan's capital Amman in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
He did not specify the time of the meeting due to what Egypt's
Middle East News Agency said the officials' engagements in the
following weeks.
</P>
<P>
The meeting comes as part of the continued discussions of and
coordination of stances on the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks
among the three parties, the Egyptian minister said.
</P>
<P>
The peace process between the Palestinians and Israel has come
to a standstill after the Jewish state froze the implementation of
the Wye accord and decided to hold early general elections on May
17.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed by the two sides last October in
Washington, Israel should withdraw from another 13 percent of the
West Bank in three phases. But the accord was suspended by Israel
only after the first phase was carried out in early December as
Israel accused the Palestinians of igniting violence against it.
</P>
<P>
Israel has threatened to shelve the accord unless the
Palestinians meeting conditions including collecting illegal
weapons, reducing police forces, which the Palestinians denounced
as requirements not stipulated in the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Jordan, the two Arab countries which have conceived
peace with Israel, have been actively mediating the peace talks
between the Palestinians and Israel. 
</P>
