<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Jordanian King Hussein and Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak are to inaugurate an electric power linkage between Egypt
and Jordan next week, to which Syria, Iraq and Turkey are also to
be bound in phases.
</P>
<P>
Last July, pre-operation tests were made after the working out
of the first phase of the international grid, whose
500,000-Kilovolt high-tension cables were extended through the
Suez Canal, the Arabic daily Al-Alam Al-Youm reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian government and the International Monetary
Fund are to finalize a 1999-2001 economic reform program next week.
</P>
<P>
Press sources said Sunday that Amman expects 200 million
U.S. dollars from the IMF to finance a three-year rectification
plan to enhance the Jordanian economy.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the plan includes cutting budget deficit,
going ahead with the privatization process, readjusting some
sectors such as water, agriculture, health, higher education,
boosting cooperation between the public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The number of passengers carried by Cyprus Airways
and its subsidiary charters company Eurocypria increased by 7.7
percent in 1998 from 1997, the Cyprus News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two companies transported 1.72 million passengers in 1998
against 1.60 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Passengers from and to Sweden marked the highest increase by
42.3 percent, followed by the Netherlands by 32.1 percent, Norway
by 25.4 percent, Italy by 24.9 percent, Greece by 19.2 percent,
Germany by 14.3 percent and Israel by 11.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Britain remains the Cyprus national carriers' biggest customer
with 491,000 people flying Cyprus Airways in 1998.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian Ministry of Health and Population and the
United Nations Population Fund signed an agreement here Sunday on
financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the U.N. fund will provide an aid worth 4
million dollars in the next three years for Egypt's health
projects, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Arab Fund for Economic Development in Africa has
agreed to provide Chad with 43 million dollars as part of the
fund's development and technical assistance for the country,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, officials of the Chadian Ministry of Planning held
talks with officials of the fund this week for another 23 million
dollars in loan for a comprehensive rural development project in
Chad's Salamat area. 
</P>
