<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Start Elephant Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Wildlife Service
(KWS) will start a five-day aerial count of elephants in the Tsavo
game park from Monday in a move to help gauge the impact of
renewed ivory trade in African elephant range countries.
</P>
<P>
Paula Kahumbu, the scientific advisor to the KWS director, said
in a statement issued Sunday that 10 aircrafts and some 40
personnel on the ground, including wildlife experts from South
Africa and Zimbabwe will take part in the census.
</P>
<P>
The tenth conference of the Convention of International Trade in
 Endangered Species (CITES), held in Harare, Zimbabwe, 1997,
re-opened an experimental ivory trade by allowing three southern
African nations to sell a shipment of ivory to Japan.
</P>
<P>
However, CITES agreed at the meeting that should elephant
populations in other African countries become threatened, the
permit would be cancelled.
</P>
<P>
But Kenya is among countries which fear that even a limited
lifting of the ban on the ivory trade will revive the large scale
poaching of earlier years.
</P>
<P>
"The need to establish the status of the Tsavo elephant
population is now imperative in order to be able to gauge the
impact of a reopening of trade in ivory,'' Kahumbu said.
</P>
<P>
The Tsavo Game Park, Kenya's largest game park, saw big threats
of the extinction of elephants by illegal poaching in the 1970s
and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
By 1988, the number of elephants in Tsavo had fallen to 5,363
from more than 45,000 in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
"After 1988, intensive anti-poaching efforts were rewarded, and
by 1994 the elephant population in Tsavo had risen to over
7,000,'' said Kahumbu.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has not had the cash until now to monitor the situation
accurately but now hopes to repeat the survey every year, he said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 21:00 GMT, January 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein Sunday called on
Asian and African countries to set up a new grouping to balance
the existing western alliances led by the United States.
</P>
<P>
In a nationally televised address on the 8th anniversary of
the 1991 Gulf War, Saddam assailed the U.S. and its western allies
for the maintenance and eastward expansion of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
He also described the mid-December U.S.-British air raids
against Iraq as the day of triumph for his regime, saying the
bombardment exposed the scheme of the enemies.
(BC-Iraq-Saddam-Address)
</P>
