<HEADLINE> Europe, India Cooperation Meeting to Be Held </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Indian business people and
entrepreneurs will soon have an opportunity to compare notes with
their European counterparts when a cooperation meeting is held in
New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
The plan of the meeting was announced here on Monday by the
joint commission of the European Union and India.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, to be known as the Europartenariat or European
cooperation, will attract more than 350 Indian companies that
expect to benefit from the European Union's Asia Invest Program
which encourages business link-ups between Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is slated for March 15 and 16.
</P>
<P>
At the time being, the European Union is India's largest
trading partner, with a 26-percent share of the country's exports
and a 25-percent share of its imports.
</P>
<P>
Two-way trade between the European Union and India has grown
from 14 billion ECU (16.3 billion U.S. dollars) in 1994 to 19.7
billion ECU (23 billion dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Though India's total imports have picked up, European Union's
exports to this Asian country have receded, resulting in a trade
deficit of 340 million ECU (397.8 million dollars) for the first
time in this decade on the part of the union, according to the
union's statistical bureau Eurostat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
