<HEADLINE> Severe Storms Kill at Least Eight People in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 18 (Xinhua) -- At least eight people were
killed and 11 others critically injured as a fierce storm system
packing several tornadoes raced across western Tennessee in the
United States on Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
Six people died when a tornado whipped through Madison County,
said Kurt Pickering, spokesman for the state's Emergency
Management Agency. At least 71 county residents were hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
Three of the deaths occurred in a subdivision south of
downtown Jackson, a town of nearly 50,000 in west-central
Tennessee. At least 60 homes and businesses in the Jackson area
were damaged or shattered. A new Tennessee National Guard armory
and two UH-60 helicopters were destroyed at McKellar-Sipes
Airport.
</P>
<P>
Officials have opened two shelters to house the victims. Extra
state troopers and military police have been dispatched to the
area.
</P>
<P>
In Henderson County, 40 kilometers east of Jackson, about 30
homes were damaged or destroyed. A woman's body was discovered in
the ruins of her home and her husband was seriously injured,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Another person was killed in Hardeman County in southwestern
Tennessee, authorities said, but details on the death were not
immediately available.
</P>
<P>
The tornadoes also cut power in many areas as high winds
ripped tree limbs and power lines.
</P>
<P>
The storm died down in Tennessee as it headed east early
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
