<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Computer Crime Uncovered in Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The hacker who inputted a
computer virus, called "logical bomb", in two sets of top selling
educational software has been detained, Beijing police said today.
</P>
<P>
This man was discovered to be a disgruntled former employee of
the company who made them, police said.
</P>
<P>
The virus, which is automatically disguised in the form of an
"exe" document, has been designed to erase data on computer hard
drives if the software is operated on every 27th day after March
27 this year.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Wuyou Software Development Co., developer of the
two computer educational software programs for A-degree national
computer grade examination, said that it has lost over 500,000
yuan because it has had to recall all of the 16,000 software
products it has so far sold.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wenming, the former director of the company's new
product development department, was picked up by police after
evidence of his crime was discovered, including the computer code
of the virus and printed documents of the program design.
</P>
<P>
Zhang has confessed and revealed that his actions were revenge
against a company director with whom he had a disagreement. He
took advantage of his power in the company to input a foreign
virus in the company's new products, which had been under
development since December last year.
</P>
<P>
The case is still being investigated and most of the software
products sold have already been returned to the company.
</P>
<P>
Wuyou has manufactured 20,000 copies of the new software and
said that news of the virus affecting its products has damaged
its reputation among customers who are mainly schools.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
