<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightens Licensing for Telecom Equipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Information
Industry (MII) today issued the first batch of special licenses
for 18 Chinese and foreign telecommunication equipment
manufacturers in a bid to combat smuggling and the marketing of
inferior goods and to encourage foreign companies to transfer
technology to China.
</P>
<P>
On January 1, China restructured the licensing system for
telecommunication equipment which previously was controlled by
several authorities, putting all the power into the hands of MII.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Chunjiang, director-general of the Bureau of
Telecommunications Administration of MII, said that past
experience proved that many overseas-funded companies failed to
meet their commitment on technology transfer and export goals.
Instead, Zhang noted that they refused or delayed technology
transfer using various excuses and sold almost every item of
their product range in the China market.
</P>
<P>
Under the new system, telecommunications equipment made by
both Chinese and foreign companies for the domestic market will
have a special tag attached to it. Products without the tag
cannot be sold or used in China.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that it is also designed to combat rampant
smuggling that threatens the survival of China's
telecommunication equipment manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
In order to prevent smugglers from attaching fake tags to
products, the tags are fitted with anti-piracy technology. MII is
to phase out all old tags under the previous licensing system
within 12 months, the first to be abolished will be those on
mobile phones, which are part of a massive smuggling racket.
</P>
<P>
Authorities will also carry out ongoing quality inspection on
the products of those companies that have obtained licenses.
</P>
<P>
In order to guarantee service quality to license applicants, M
II has set up two administration centers in Beijing. It has also
abolished the practice of issuing licenses on the quota basis.
Instead, various models can be sold in unlimited amounts.
</P>
<P>
Among the first companies that obtained licenses today are
Shanghai Bell, Motorola and Nokia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0047 </DOCNO>
