<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Score Remarkable Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks gained 2.5
percent today following a rebound on Wall Street as a result of
the Brazilian government's decision to float the real which has
helped boost major stock markets.
</P>
<P>
The main Hang Seng Index increased 255.14 points, or 2.51
percent, to close at 10,402.54 today. The index suffered a steep
fall of 575.3 points, or 5.36 percent, last week triggered by the
financial crisis in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Banking shares led the upward trend with an increase of 438.61
points, or 3.08 percent, followed by property, commercial and
industrial, and utilities counters, each advanced by over two
percent.
</P>
<P>
Today's turnover was much thinner, at 3,824 million HK dollars
(490 million U.S. dollars), as against Friday's turnover of 5,197
million HK dollars (666 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index opened the week's trading 208.66 points,
or 2.06 percent, higher at 10,356.06 this morning.  
</P>
