<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Engineering Consultants Reject Projects Without Approval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China's fledgling engineering
consultancy sector is being encouraged to say "no" to projects
which don't have approval in a bid to avoid mistakes and ensure
the smooth implementation of the state's macroeconomic goals.
</P>
<P>
To stimulate the economy, China will focus on increasing
investments in infrastructure this year to expand domestic
consumer demand. Experts predict that investment in fixed assets
in 1999 will most probably excel that of last year's
approximately 2.8 trillion yuan as the central government has
decided to continue pro-active fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
So, in the early stages, consultancy for many projects,
especially key state projects, as well as project management and
quality, has become an important factor in stabilizing
macroeconomic growth and enabling the right decisions to be made.
</P>
<P>
The three-day second session of the China National Association
of Engineering Consultants, which began here today, focuses on
how the sector will provide better services for government
departments and various project owners taking into account the
current difficult economic situation.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the opening ceremony, Li Rongrong,
vice-minister of the State Development Planning Commission, asked
the consultancy sector to help promote China's investment and
capital pooling system reform, starting with project quality.
</P>
<P>
The sector should also get actively involved in mapping out
the 10th Five-Year Plan (2001-2005) and macroeconomic control
policies, as well as in research areas of great significance, Li
said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the sector to provide all round and through-process
consulting for projects, especially those involving key state
infrastructure, to help the government guarantee the quality of
preliminary project consultancy and appraisal in a move to
effectively speed up economic development and avoid waste of
effort in construction.
</P>
<P>
Over a long period of time, decision-making on major
infrastructure projects was mainly made by central and local
leaders without any consultation. Beginning in the early 1980s,
China introduced the consultany practice which incorporated the
need for feasibility studies. Now, some 2,000 approved
consultancy companies in China have opened up with the emphasis
on ensuring that the right decisions are made in advance of
actions being taken.
</P>
<P>
Practice shows that projects which have enjoyed consultancy
advice have yielded good results. However, some projects turned
out to be a failure as the consultancies involved gave the go
ahead merely so that they could benefit, along with the owners.
</P>
<P>
Sector insiders are now calling for much tighter control over
this kind of malpractice.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
