<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Still Mulling About Nagano Games Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The skaters who desperately wanted to end China's winter
Olympic gold drought were once again hurtled to the ground when
they
only managed five silvers in Nagano despite they had triumphed in
a series of world-level competitions and produced a couple of
world records in their run-up to the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
"I've never thought of finishing without a single gold with so
many world class skaters in the team," Xin Qingshan, head coach
of the Chinese national team, said during the China's Ninth
National Winter Games here.
</P>
<P>
Xin, 38, who started his short track coaching career in 1983,
ascribed the loss mostly to his coaching ability.
</P>
<P>
"I'm the one to blame most. I didn't expect such a big loss,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The other reason is tactical immaturity of the skaters, for
it's the first Olympics for most of them," he added.
</P>
<P>
Yang Yang (S), who won three silvers in women's 500-, 1,000-
and 3,000-meter relay in Nagano, said she would never forget the
feeling in the Olympic Games. "I was so nervous that I could
hardly control my movements," said the two-time Olympian.
</P>
<P>
"I have benefited a lot from the Olympic experience," said
Yang Yang (A), who took a silver in the women's 1,000m in Nagano.
"Now I am no longer afraid to compete against South Koreans or
Canadians."
</P>
<P>
Yang Yang (A), who led the national squad to their best-ever
World Cup performance in 1998, won the overall champion in the
World Cup Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
Yang Yang (S) and Wang Chunlu finished second and third
respectively in the World Cup overall rankings last season while
Li Jiajun topped the men's overall standings.
</P>
<P>
"We shifted our training method by concentrating on the
understanding of the rules and the comprehensive capability for
the competition," said the 24-year-old Li.
</P>
<P>
"A nation-wide known psychologist gives us class every week
and we study video tape recording of competitions three times a
week," added Li, who narrowly missed the Olympic title as South
Korean Kim Dong-Sung stuck out his right foot from behind at the
finish to win the men's 1,000m in Nagano. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
