<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tiananmen Square Face-lift Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The long awaited renovation of
Beijing's famous Tiananmen Square was kick-started today when the
first new paving stone was laid in the world's largest city
square.
</P>
<P>
Huge industrial machines and busy workers have replaced
tourists on the 880 meters long and 500 meters wide square, and
stacks of pink granite slabs are piled up near the Mao Zedong
Memorial Hall.
</P>
<P>
The first paving stone was laid within the confines of the
memorial hall. All the old stones will be replaced by special
new ones, shipped in from nearby Hebei province.
</P>
<P>
They are said to be wear and tear proof and have a more
beautiful finish.
</P>
<P>
Last year city authorities said that the Memorial Hall will
reopen on March 15, 1999, so the renovation of that area must be
completed efficiently.
</P>
<P>
Renovation of the whole square will be completed by July
ready for the grand celebrations to mark the 50th anniversary of
the founding of the People's Republic on October 1.
</P>
<P>
The project includes replacing paving slabs throughout the
square as well as around the confines of the Mao Zedong Memorial
Hall, improving lighting around the periphery of the square,
renewing the loudspeaker systems, installing new fountains and
repairing underground pipelines.
</P>
<P>
The goal is to end up with a 21st century style square which
will reflect China's modern, new capital which was once the
center of the world in ancient times.
</P>
<P>
The first renovation of the Tiananmen square took place in
1959 to celebrate the 10th anniversary of the founding of New
China but much of the square is now out of date and it needed
upgrading to maintain its political and historical importance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
