<HEADLINE> Beijing Economy Grows by 9.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's economy grew by a
remarkable 9.7 percent in 1998 over the previous year to reach
some 200.9 billion yuan (about 25 billion U.S. dollars), despite
the negative influence of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The figure exceeds the nine-percent target set by the
municipal government at the beginning of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Liu Qi, deputy major of Beijing, attributed the achievement to
the surging internal market demands as well as the investments in
infrastructure. Increased bonds and bank loans have also
contributed to the result.
</P>
<P>
An average Beijing resident's annual income hit 8,500 yuan
(about 1,000 U.S. dollars) in 1998, an increase of 6.3 percent.
</P>
