<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Witnesses Rapid Insurance Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China's total insurance
premiums for 1998 reached 124.73 billion yuan, up 14 percent from
the previous year, according to statistics released here today by
the China Insurance Regulatory commission (CIRC).
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the premiums for property insurance was 49.96 billion
yuan, up three percent over 1997, while that for health and
accidental injuries insurance increased 18 percent to 6.5 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
By the end of September of 1998, the total assets of the
insurance sector reached 199.08 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China's insurance sector has enjoyed rapid development over
the past few years in line with the deepening of the reform and
opening policies, with the premiums rising by 37.6 percent
annually, according to Ma Yongwei, President of the CIRC.
</P>
<P>
Ma said that the insurance sector has made a great
contribution to the country's economic and social development, as
it paid business tax of 4.82 billion yuan and various
compensations worth 55.59 billion yuan in 1998.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the year there were 25 insurance companies set
up, including four state-owned, nine private share-holding, and
12 overseas-funded, which offered cover for 1,000 different items.
</P>
<P>
The sector continued its efforts to open to the outside world,
and so far, 14 overseas-funded insurance companies have been or
are being set up in the country.
</P>
<P>
In addition to that, 113 foreign companies from 17 countries
have set up 202 representative offices in China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, domestic insurance firms have also spared no
efforts in tapping the overseas market. By the end of last year,
Chinese insurance companies had set up 33 branches and eight
representative offices overseas.
</P>
<P>
Ma acknowledged that the country's insurance market also faces
some problems, such as poor management and needed an improvement
in its assets quality. He pointed out that the CIRC will
strengthen its efforts to standardize the market to guard against
risk.
</P>
<P>
According to Ma, the sector will pay more attention to
readjust insurance structures and improve its management to make
firms more competitive on the domestic and world markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
