<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's Largest Rehab Service Center Opens in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee
Hwa of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) today
opened the largest rehabilitation service center in Asia, the
Tung Wah Group of Hospitals Jockey Club Rehabilitation Complex in
Aberdeen, Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The complex comprises 25 service units with a total of 1,410
day-time and residential places for people with disabilities. It
helps increase the rehabilitation services for the aged with
visual impairment and mentally handicapped and physically
disabled persons.
</P>
<P>
The total capital cost for the complex amounted to about 510
million HK dollars (65.38 million U.S. dollars), of which 332
million HK dollars (42.56 million U.S. dollars) was from the
Lotteries Fund and the remaining 178 million HK dollars (22.82
million U.S. dollars) from the Hong Kong Jockey Club Charities
Trust.
</P>
<P>
The whole complex occupies a total floor space of 40,000
square meters. It consists of five service blocks and houses 25
adult rehabilitation services units.
</P>
<P>
Different types of rehabilitation services are provided,
including a sheltered workshop and two hostels for the moderately
mentally handicapped, three care and attention homes for the
severely disabled, six day activity centers and six hostels for
the severely mentally handicapped and seven homes for the
visually impaired elderly.
</P>
<P>
Katherine Fok, secretary for health and welfare of the SAR,
who also attended the opening ceremony, said the SAR government
has pledged to provide more than 400 additional day-time and
residential places for people with disabilities in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to providing quality rehabilitation services
to meet the needs of people with disabilities," Fok said.
</P>
</TEXT>
