<HEADLINE> Russia Condemns New Killings in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov said on Monday that he was alarmed by the discovery of the
bodies of 45 ethnic Albanians in the Kosovo village of Racak on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting with visiting Cuban Foreign Minister
Roberto Robaina Gonzalez, Ivanov voiced his deep concern over the
new escalation of tension in Kosovo, saying that Moscow "strongly
condemns any expressions of terrorism and violence no matter
where they originate".
</P>
<P>
He urged the Yugoslav authorities to work with independent
international experts to "investigate thoroughly all the
circumstances of the tragic incident that occurred in Kosovo and
find out reasons behind this tragedy".
</P>
<P>
"These tragic events cannot be viewed in isolation," the minis
ter said. "It is a link in a chain of events which have occurred
in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
He called for direct negotiations between Belgrade and the
Kosovo Albanian leadership, saying that "the political settlement
in Kosovo has been slipping".
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Russian First Deputy Foreign
Minister Alexander Avdeyev is expected to go to Belgrade shortly,
possibly on Tuesday, for talks with Yugoslav leaders, Interfax
reported, quoting informed sources.
</P>
<P>
Avdeyev's visit was planned before the latest killing of
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, but his talks with the Belgrade
leaders will focus on the discovery of 45 murdered Albanians in
Kosovo over the weekend, Interfax said. 
