<HEADLINE> Defense Lawyers Withdraw from Lesotho Mutiny Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- All six defense lawyers
have withdrawn from the trial of 50 Lesotho soldiers in Maseru,
capital of Lesotho, South African Press Association reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the soldiers' legal team, Khalaki Sello
said they withdrew because they objected to the trial being held
within the precinct of a maximum security prison.
</P>
<P>
"A trial within a prison could send only one signal that the
accused would spend some time at the place," Sello said.
</P>
<P>
There was a sharp exchange between Sello and the judge-advocate
Brendan Cullinan, after Sello claimed the trial was a political
one.
</P>
<P>
Sello said the charges were political since the soldiers were
not being tried for murder or stock theft, but he later withdrew
this accusation.
</P>
<P>
The hearing was adjourned until Tuesday to enable the accused
to decide on alternative legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
The 50 soldiers have been charged with mutiny following an
uprising in the Lesotho Defense Force in September last year, when
junior officers dismissed nearly 30 senior officers.
</P>
<P>
The junior officers arrested the commander of the Lesotho
Defense Force and forced him to make a statement over Radio
Lesotho that he had dismissed the senior officers and that he had
personally resigned.
</P>
<P>
This led to widespread unrest erupting on September 22 which a
task force from South Africa and Botswana were sent to quell.
</P>
</TEXT>
