<HEADLINE> Revolution of Learning, Reference Not Guidance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The controversial book
"Revolution of Learning" should only be regarded as a reference
work rather than as a definitive guide for everyone, said a
Chinese scientist.
</P>
<P>
If everyone thinks and studies in the way mentioned in the
book, it will be contradictory to the book's theme, which is
"innovation", said Prof. Yang Xiongli, an expert with the
Shanghai Research Institute of Physiology.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese company has said it will invest a total of 100
million yuan (about 12 million U.S. dollars) into the sales
promotion of the book throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Yang has also showed dissatisfaction over some
misinterpretation in the translated version of the book. In an
extreme case, the Chinese version of the book said "the ce
rebellum, or brain stem controls many of your instincts, such as
breathing and heart beat." But even a middle school student knows
that the cerebellum is in charge of the body's motor senses.
</P>
<P>
"It is acceptable for the 'Revolution of Learning' to suggest
that study is the only way to adjust oneself to the information
society," Yang said, "but it is misleading for it to advocate the
same learning style for everybody."
</P>
<P>
He said he does not agree with the Chinese promoter of the
book, who claimed that they will sell 10 million copies of the
book in China which it hoped would allow the whole of the
nation's younger generation to study in accordance with the
book's methods.
</P>
<P>
It is also unacceptable if administrative and education
departments are involved in the promotion activities, said Yang,
who is also an academician of the China Academy of Sciences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
