<HEADLINE> Possible Suspect for China Bus Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- An unidentified man, who
could be a rural migrant, might be responsible for the bus
explosion which left four people seriously wounded last night in
this capital of central China's Hunan province.
</P>
<P>
Eye-witness, Fu Yong, a 16-year-old student, said that he saw
the man put a lighted cigarette into a big sack he had brought
onto the bus, and then the sack exploded.
</P>
<P>
"The young man looked like a farmer who was in the city
looking for temporary work. He was dressed in tatty clothing and
was generally scruffy. He smoked continuously as he traveled and
when the bus approached a major stop, he put the dog-end into a
sack he had with him, got off the bus and the explosion
followed." added Fu.
</P>
<P>
But police did not confirm this account, saying that the
incident is still being investigated.
</P>
<P>
Thirty seven passengers were hurt, including four severely.
Hospital sources said that after emergency treatment all were now
out of danger.
</P>
<P>
The most severely wounded was a 40-year-old woman who lost
both her legs. She was in a state of shock after losing too much
blood, according to Li Yuedong, an executive of the Changsha No.1
People's Hospital. Surgeons were forced to amputate her legs to
save her life. Another two persons have now also had legs
amputated.
</P>
<P>
Others whose eardrums were affected by the explosion have
undergone surgery.  
</P>
</TEXT>
