<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Muslims in Somalia Celebrate Eid-Al-Fitri </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Somali capital Mogadishu
is made very colorful Monday by thousands of people cheering and
chanting to celebrate the occasion of Eid-Al-Fitri following the
culmination of the Holy month of Ramadan on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Children wore new clothes and blew sirens and balloons, while
hundreds more of them played with toy guns and pistols
impersonating the street fighters of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The main mosques of the capital and the major towns of Somalia
mainly read the Takbiir which is always recited on the two Islamic
holy festivals, Eld Al-Fitri and the Eid Al-Ad-ha on the
pilgrimage season.
</P>
<P>
Families paid visits to their relatives and shared large meals
and sweets with them, while the poor were offered food alms and
money. However, as usual, everything is disputed in Somalia be it
political, social or religious especially since the civil war
began in the country nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
An Islamic group which calls itself "Ahlu Sunna Wal-Jama" had
been asking people on Sunday night not to recognize the sighting
of the moon by the other religious groups and the ordinary
civilians as well. Messages to refuse the Eid Al-Fitri had been
broadcast Sunday night on a radio run by Ahlu Sunna Wal-Jama in
south Mogadishu calling on the people to continue fasting and
fulfill their daily obligations,
</P>
<P>
Early Monday morning as most of the mosques began reciting the
Takbiir, others have opened their business stalls and Koranic
schools ordering their demoralized offspring to take their daily
lessons in accordance with the norms of their affiliated group's
wishes. Nonetheless, there has not been any face-to-face dispute
or disturbances anywhere in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The Eid Al-Fitri was exceptionally observed in the main street
of Makka Al-Mukarramah in the heart of the city known as Bermuda
neighborhood, where the governor of the disputed administration
of Mogadishu, Hussein Ali Ahmed, has opened it for circulation
after nine years of closure due to the civil strife.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people strolled in the street gingerly just to see
how devastating the war had been. Over 70 percent of Bermuda area
had been ruined by clan clashes in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Ali Ahmed also inaugurated a new campaign in cleaning the
street of Makka Al-Mukarraniah Sunday. Over 40 trucks and
hundreds of volunteers took their brooms and baskets to get rid of
the sand which covered the tarmac road.  According to reports,
the opening of the road followed an underground negotiation
between Ali Ahmed and elders from the area for a possible full
deployment of police force in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
Similar celebrations took place in the main towns of Kismaio,
Merca, Garoweh, Bossaso, Baidoa and Beletuein where local people
have read the Takbiir for several hours before the Eid Prayers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
