<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Falls 5.3 Percent in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus
fell to 1,207.7 billion yen (10 billion U.S. dollars) in November
last year, down 5.3 percent from a year earlier, the Finance
Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The current account surplus, the broadest gauge of trade in
goods and services, shrank for the first time in seven months, as
calculated before adjustments for seasonal variations.
</P>
<P>
A 13.4 percent fall in the trade surplus from a year earlier
helped push down the current account surplus.
</P>
<P>
Exports in November plunged 12.8 percent while imports tumbled
12.5 percent from a year before, the ministry said in a
preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
The setback in Japan's exports was attributable mainly to
slack demand in crisis-hit Asian countries, while the drop in
imports reflects falling crude oil prices and weak domestic
demand resulting from the recession, a ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the United States, Japan's largest trade partner,
dropped by 7.1 percent, the first year-on-year decline in two ye
ars and eight months.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials said it would take time to judge whether
there was a reversal in Japan's trade picture.
</P>
<P>
"We have to monitor the situation for a little longer before
judging what the trend will be in the future," an official said.
</P>
<P>
In November, the yen averaged 120.58 against one U.S. dollar,
compared with 125.27 yen a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
