<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flight to Lhasa, One of China's Most Comfortable Air Journeys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Aboard the A-340 Airbus headed
for Lhasa, capital of southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region,
even passengers with much flying experience can find anything to
complain about, except perhaps for the early time of departure.
</P>
<P>
Passengers are obliged to rush to the airport before dawn in
order to catch the plane, which leaves Chengdu, capital of
southwestern Sichuan Province, at 6:40 a.m. every morning.
</P>
<P>
Flight 4401 is currently the only air route linking the
Tibetan capital to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
"Flights to Lhasa must take off in early morning to avoid
possible dangers caused by the increasing air turbulence over the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau after sunrise," said an official with the
China Southwestern Airlines, which has been running the
Chengdu-Lhasa air route since its debut more than 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
But according to a passenger named Liu, who often takes
domestic flights on business trips, the flight to Lhasa still
ranks among the country's most comfortable air journeys.
</P>
<P>
The plane has large, comfortable seats and an advanced
audio-video system, he said, while the in-flight service is also
first class.
</P>
<P>
"I never expected such a smooth and comfortable flight over
the Roof of the World," he added.
</P>
<P>
When the Chengdu-Lhasa air route was first opened, a journey
to Lhasa was an ordeal for every passenger, and the small plane
bought from the former Soviet Union could only carry 90 people
each flight, a China Southwestern senior official recalled.
</P>
<P>
"Now my plane can accommodate 370 passengers, with
state-of-the-art navigation and communication systems," said Yi
Daqi, chief pilot of Flight 4401 for the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
To provide a better service for Tibetan passengers, Yi and his
crew members are now studying the Tibetan language in their spare
time.
</P>
<P>
"The plane is good, so is the service. Actually there is
certainly nothing about it to upset anyone," Julien Temple, a
representative from Handicap International, commented when the
plane landed in Lhasa at 8:30 a.m., bang on schedule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
