<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Police Smashes Counterfeit Money Gang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua ) -- The Chaoyang Branch of
Beijing Municipal Bureau of Public Security has solved a major
case involving the trafficking of counterfeit Chinese currency
and confiscated about 110,000 yuan worth of forged notes.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman for the bureau, the police arrested
four suspects, leaving the man believed to be the overall
mastermind, Nie Yong, a native of southwest China's Sichuan
Province, still at large.
</P>
<P>
The four suspects are Pang Shuyan, Liu Minglu, Zeng Guangfu and
Nie Yong's elder brother Nie Bin. The illegal activities were
first brought to their attention from the area around Chongwenmen
District after members of the public provided information.
</P>
<P>
Pang and Liu were caught red-handed as they tried to trade
counterfeit yuan notes for genuine ones and later police also
found 106,000 yuan worth of counterfeit money, all in 50-yuan
denominations, in Nie Yong's house.
</P>
<P>
Police say the notes, which were today sent to the People's
Bank of China for checking, will be destroyed by the bank later.
</P>
<P>
Chinese laws stipulate that people found guilty of trafficking
counterfeit money over 100 yuan in value will be given a sentence
of re-education through labor. For higher denominations the
punishment will fit the level of the crime.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, more than six million yuan worth of counterfeit money
was confiscated by Beijing's departments of public security,
banking and postal and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Most of the counterfeit notes confiscated by Beijing police
are made in south China's Guangdong Province and central China's
Henan Province. Some of the counterfeit notes are so perfect
that it is hard to tell them from the genuine.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
