<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Agriculture Expected to Grow 5.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is expected to
achieve its target of a 5.4-percent growth in the agriculture
sector in the current fiscal year ending on June 30, 1999, sources
from the Planning Commission said Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, the growth rate may slide in case of any downward
revision of wheat output owning to delayed winter rain, said the
sources.
</P>
<P>
The post-rain situation of wheat crops is yet to be
ascertained, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
"As far as the rice is concerned, we have achieved the target,"
the sources said, adding that "the reports received so far suggest
that we are right on target regarding sugarcane."
</P>
<P>
But the delayed winter rain has seemingly disrupted the overall
forecast of the agriculture growth rate target, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the long spell of fog that gripped the country in
December has definitely affected the cotton crops and the target
of 10 million bales is certain to be revised downward, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Based on various indications, the sources said, the cotton
production is estimated at 9.2 million bales and may go down
further.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan achieved an agriculture growth rate of 5.9 percent
during the fiscal year of 1997-98, compared with a modest increase
of 0.6 percent in the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Out of the gross domestic product of the country, the
agriculture sector took a lion's share of 24.6 percent in the
financial year of 1997-98. 
</P>
</TEXT>
