<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China-Made Bicycles Popular in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China-made bicycles have become
increasingly popular in Bangladesh for its high quality and
accounts for 20-25 percent of the Bangladesh market at present.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh now imports about 100,000 bicycles from China each
year, a sharp increase from 15,000-20,000 four years ago, Mizanur
Rahman, managing director of Meghna Group, the sole agent of
China's famous Phoenix-brand bicycles, told Xinhua on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of the bicycles were purchased by government and
non-government institutions and some were sold in the countryside,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 90,000 bicycles were imported from China during the first
nine months of last year, but sales dropped during the last
quarter of the year due to the prolonged flood hitting the country
between July and September and the devaluation of the country's
currency, the taka, by 6 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that sales of China-made bicycles would pick up
soon when people's purchasing power is recovered.
</P>
<P>
The price of China-manufactured bicycles is a bit high, Rahman
said, adding that this sometimes gave way to India-made bicycles
that were much cheaper.
</P>
<P>
China-made bicycles are sold for 3,700-3,800 taka (about
76.29-78.35 U.S. dollars) each while an India-made one would cost
only 2,000-2,500 taka (about 41.24-51.55 dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
One way to expand the share of Chinese bicycles in the
Bangladesh market of some 400,000 items a year is to set up joint
ventures, which could reduce the cost of production and increase
the product's competitiveness, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
