<HEADLINE> China Modernizes Meteorological Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China has achieved substantial
progress in meteorological modernization and research, with
meteorological monitoring and services approaching or reaching
levels in moderately developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Wen Kegang, director of China Meteorological Bureau, made the
comments during a recent national meeting held in Xi'an, capital
of northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The fact that China is one of the few countries capable of
building and launching weather satellites represents the nation's
advanced level in related research, according to Wen.
</P>
<P>
The investment-pofit ratio for China's meteorological sector
jumped from 1:20 in the early 1980s to 1:40, said Wen, adding
that accurate and timely weather forecasts provided an important
foundation for China's battle against the record summer flooding
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
He said a number of meteorological programs have been listed
as key research projects, and noted that China's accuracy rate on
weather forecasting is expected to grow another 5-10 percent on
the current level of 60 percent when the projects are completed
by the year 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
