<HEADLINE> Australian Minister Sees Majority Support for Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The federal cabinet minister
for finance and administration, John Fahey, Monday predicted that
the majority of Australians will favor an Australian head of state
in the November referendum.
</P>
<P>
Employment Services Minister Tony Abbott Sunday stirred up
pro-republicans in the coalition by declaring that the republic
movement was driven by the chattering classes in the country and
republicans thought non-republic Australia was the "arse end of
the earth."
</P>
<P>
Fahey argued that pro-monarchist Abbott has every right to
express his views on the republic in a colorful way, but he denied
that support for the republic is limited to the chattering
classes.
</P>
<P>
Fahey followed Environment Minister Robert Hill in declaring
his determination to support the "Yes" vote when the republican
question is put in the November 6 referendum.
</P>
<P>
Like Hill, Fahey disputed Abbott's claim that coalition
ministers would be unlikely to give priority to the republic and
that the referendum would fail.
</P>
<P>
"I think the majority of Australians in fact do favor having an
Australian citizen as our head of state," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's supported by a broad cross-section of Australians, those
who believe that we have a right to seek a national identity, that
we are mature enough as a nation to say for the 21st century that
the head of state should be an Australian citizen," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fahey was the only other known pro-republican apart from Hill
in the cabinet to come out fighting Monday. Treasurer Peter
Costello and Workplace Relations Minister Peter Reith remained
silent while Abbott declined to add to his comments.
</P>
<P>
Australian Republican Movement (ARM) Chairman Malcolm Turnbull
said support for a republic within the government has grown since
last February's Constitutional Convention.
</P>
<P>
"There is obviously a variety of views within the coalition
government about the republic, but support within the government
for an Australian head of state has been growing over the past 12
months," he said.
</P>
<P>
The republican issue seems set to remain on the agenda for the
next few weeks. Opposition leader Kim Beazley is also planning an
Australia Day speech in Sydney on the republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
