<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cairo, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Aurec, one of the three major cable TV companies in
Israel, has announced its intention to target the domestic phone
market as soon as it opens to competition, the local daily Haaretz
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- British Airways has acquiesced to a request from
the Israeli Transport Ministry to extend its weekend
discount-flight program to include Thursday evenings in a bid to
enable observant Jews to take advantage of the low costs, the
local daily Haaretz reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's unemployment rate stood at 8.5 percent in
November last year, official statistics show.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate between August and November was 8.5 percent,
slightly down from 8.6 percent during the March to July period.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemen's fish production increased from 105,000 tonnes
in 1996 to 120,000 tonnes in 1998 and the figure is expected to
reach 168,000 tonnes in the year 2000, said Yemeni Minister of
Fisheries Ahmed Musaid Hussain.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published in Monday's local press, the minister
said that about 90 percent of the fish products, valued at about
25 billion Yemeni rials (1.4 billion U.S. dollars), is locally
consumed.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also sent a report to the cabinet on a new
strategy for the exploitation and protection of fisheries from the
acts of maritime piracy, said the minister. 
</P>
