<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launches Its Own Cellular Phone Handset </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China's first domestically
developed mobile telephone went on sale today.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured by the Xiamen Overseas Chinese Mobile
Communication Equipment Corp. Ltd.,in Xiamen in east China's
Fujian province, the Huaxia No 1." GSM handset is priced at
about half that of foreign makes.
</P>
<P>
The company's President Guo Zeli said that technologically it
ranks with middle or top of the range international models but
will be very competitive in the Chinese market because of its
relatively low cost.
</P>
<P>
He predicts that the launch of the handset will trigger
another round of fierce competition in China's mobile telephone
market.
</P>
<P>
Xie Linzhen, an official with the Ministry of Information
Industry (MII), remarked that it marked a great leap forward in
China's efforts to develop its own mobile communications industry.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, the number of mobile telephone users in
China had topped 25 million and sales income of mobile
communications exceeded those of local and long distance
landlines.
</P>
<P>
MII forecasts that by 2000, the number of cellular telephone
users in China will grow to 40 million.
</P>
<P>
However, at present most of the dozen or so mobile telephone
manufacturers in China are wholly or partially owned by overseas
companies.
</P>
<P>
Xie said that the Chinese-made handsets are faced with strong
competition from foreign products and stressed that domestic
manufacturers have to improve their performance-price ratio to
obtain a larger market share.
</P>
<P>
The Xiamen Overseas Chinese Mobile Communication Equipment
Corp. Ltd., is a joint venture between the Xiamen Overseas
Chinese Electronic Co. Ltd., the biggest exporter of color TV
sets in China, and the Guangzhou Communication Research
Institute.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou Research Institute is the only one that has the
technologies able to write software for mobile phones in Asia. It
began developing handsets in 1991, a year before China introduced
the first mobile telephone systems from overseas.
</P>
<P>
Several Chinese companies such as Dongfang Telecommunications
and Shenzhen Kejian have also developed a range of commercial
mobile phones and other major Chinese electronics companies such
as Konca, Haire and TCL are well ahead with their own development
plans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
