<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Foundation Promotes Hepatitis Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A new hepatitis control
foundation established in the Chinese capital plans to provide
free vaccines for poverty-stricken children.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Foundation for Hepatitis Prevention and Control
(CFHPC) will offer free hepatitis B vaccines for children in poor
and remote areas, as well as for the children of parents declared
redundant by state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The foundation at the Chinese Academy of Preventive Medicine
will also raise funds to support scientific research and
educational activities.
</P>
<P>
China allocates between 30-50 billion yuan (3.6-6 billion U.S.
dollars) annually for treatment of various types of hepatitis,
according to Professor Su Chong'ao, secretary-general of the
CFHPC.
</P>
<P>
China reportedly faces a serious epidemic of A-E hepatitis,
with more than 600 million Chinese, or half of the country's
population, infected by hepatitis B. Some 120 million individuals
carry the HB virus, with a fourth of carriers expected to
contract liver diseases, according to Su.
</P>
<P>
He said some 12 million Chinese contract liver diseases, with
over 300,000 dying from related diseases each year.
</P>
<P>
"Some 40 percent of pregnant women carrying the HB virus will
bear carriers of the virus," according to Su.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that nationwide vaccinations among newborns
would reduce the proportion of HBV carriers to under one percent
within 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Su pointed out the vaccination campaign initiated in 1992 has
effectively blocked the spread of hepatitis B amongst newborns. "
The problem now is the inability of poverty-stricken families to
shoulder the 20-yuan cost for each vaccination."
</P>
<P>
The foundation has received donations of 12.8 million yuan,
including cash, drugs and vaccines, from pharmaceutical companies
and individuals both at home and abroad.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
