<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Tourist Industry Hit by Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Asia's economic crisis cost
Australian tourism up to 665 million Australian dollars (about 420
million U.S. dollars) in the first 11 months in 1998, despite
increased business from the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary Australian Bureau of Statistics data released
Monday showed that visitors to Australia from overseas fell by 4.2
percent to 3.7 million in the 11 months to November 1998, compared
with the same period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Arrivals from Northeast and Southeast Asia both recorded falls
over that period, down by 16.8 and 18.5 percent to 1.1 million and
 482,000 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Tourism Council Australia (TCA) said there was no doubt the
sector had been hit hard by the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"This equates to a loss in revenue of around 665 million
Australian dollars which has meant a tough 1998 for many tourism
businesses," TCA Chairman John Schaap said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea led the fall in tourist arrivals from Asia,
recording a decline of 74.5 percent to 57,100, followed by
Indonesia, down 44.7 percent to 81,600; Thailand, 32.8 percent to
42,200; and Malaysia, down 23.4 percent to 99,600.
</P>
<P>
But arrivals from the United States rose 13.3 percent to
337,200 while those from New Zealand and Europe went up by 4.1 and
8.8 percent to 650,800 and 820,900 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Tourist Commission (ATC) said the United States
and Europe remained the best performing regions in 1998 for the
Australian inbound tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
ATC Director John Morse said growth from the two traditional
regions and the vital New Zealand market insulated the industry
from much of the pain of the Asian economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
"The statistics put Australia on track to record just a
4-percent decline in international visitor arrivals in 1998,"
Morse said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
