<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher on Wall Street Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
moved higher Monday, inspired by Wall Street's Friday rally, with
blue-chip industrial stocks leading the way.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index finished 21.1 points firmer
at 2,830.4.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials added 51 points to 5,090.3 but the all
resources index missed the boat, falling 6.8 points to 980.9.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average index surged 219.62
points to 9,340.55, largely fueled by the Brazilian government's
decision to float its sinking currency, the real.
</P>
<P>
"We clearly moved on the back of Wall Street today," Henderson
Charlton Jones broker Brett O'Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
"Resources were weak, led by the gold sector, with ongoing
negative sentiment there," he said.
</P>
<P>
Diversified resources major BHP shed 9.4 cents to 12.10
Australian dollars, and global miner Rio Tinto came off 16.1 cents
to 19.555 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold sector lost 13.5 points or 1.2 percent to 1,092.7.
</P>
<P>
The price of gold bullion closed trading in Sydney at 287.15
U.S. dollars per fine ounce compared to Friday's close of 286.40
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector was strong, gaining 85 points or 1.3 percent
to 6,491.2.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank jumped 25 cents to 25.42 Australian
dollars, ANZ recovered 19 cents for 10.47 Australian dollars,
Commonwealth Bank of Australia ended 29.5 cents stronger at 22.85
Australian dollars, and Westpac bank spiked 20.4 cents to 11.02
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover reached 290.47 million shares valued at
478.06 million U.S. dollars. Rises outpaced falls 637 to 495 and
382 stocks were steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
