<HEADLINE> Australian Navy Seeks Fund for Submarine Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Royal Australian Navy
(RAN) is considering asking for more federal funding to iron out
problems with the weapons system of its six Collins submarines.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to ask the cabinet to top up the
5-billion-Australian-dollar (3.15 billion U.S. dollars) submarine
construction program, which was originally written in 1985 to
upgrade combat capabilities, was "still under consideration within
the department," an RAN spokesman said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Essentially, it's an enhancement of the combat system and
other aspects of the submarines," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
A report published in The Australian Monday said that the RAN
was forced to renegotiate its contract with the Australian
Submarine Corporation to bring the computerized weapons system to
an acceptable standard.
</P>
<P>
The weapons system has been plagued with problems over the
course of the project.
</P>
<P>
The main problem with the combat system lies in its tactical
data-handling system, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
To overcome the problems, the Defense Department is to seek the
cabinet's approval for about 50 million Australian dollars (31.5
million U.S. dollars) for a new project to "augment" the combat
system for the six Collins-class submarines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
