<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Fares Well in Swimming World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
World champion Ian Thorpe grabbed the 400m freestyle while
fellow Australian Susan O'Neil triumphed in the women's 200m
freestyle final.
</P>
<P>
Thorpe, 16, unbeaten in major 400 freestyles since winning the
world championship title in Perth last January, trailed
compatriot Grant Hackett until the last 25 meters before storming
to victory in three minutes 42.19 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Hackett, who was under world record pace at the halfway stage,
appeared jaded after the last turn and finished second in 3:43.40.
</P>
<P>
"That was a really good swim for me," Thorpe said. "I'm
incredibly happy with that. Grant swam that race really well and
I had to come over the top and catch him. Fortunately, once
again, I was able to do that."
</P>
<P>
O'Neil clocked 1:58.87 to win the women's 200m freestyle,
beating Sweden's Josefin Lillhage and Louise Johnke into second
and third spot respectively.
</P>
<P>
Australia's other gold medals came from Matthew Dunn in the
men's 400m individual medley, William Kirby in the men's 200m
butterfly, Ryan Mitchell in the men's 200m backstroke, Giaan
Rooney in the women's 50m backstroke and Rachel Jarris in the
women's 800m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
With host country run-away leader in the gold standings,
Germany and Sweden shared the second spot with the same haul of
three. The United States picked two golds with South Africa and
Canada taking one apiece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
