<HEADLINE> Book Clubs Thrive in Major Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The number of book clubs which
began to thrive in major Chinese cities late last year has topped
80 at present with a total membership of 700,000.
</P>
<P>
In the Chinese capital alone, four new books clubs were
established between August and October 1998, sources here said
today.
</P>
<P>
The Xishu Club, the first book society established in Beijing
in July 1997, currently has 50,000 members.
</P>
<P>
An atlas club founded in Beijing last August is now well
received among its members which include technical personnel as
well as soldiers, workers and farmers. A Shanghai-based club
which is tied with a German book society recently announced its
membership list has grown to 600,000.
</P>
<P>
Members pay an initial entry fee and then can order the latest
discounted publications by mail. Members of the Xishu Club have
access to special discounts as high as 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 78 percent of club members have completed
higher education. The clubs regularly organize discussion of
best-selling books and items of special interest, according to
the sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
