<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Withdraws Bid to Host World Expo 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines Monday
officially withdrew its bid to host World Expo 2002 after the
private sector failed to meet President Joseph Estrada's condition
to shoulder the entire cost of the global fair.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Spokesperson Jerry Barican told reporters here
Monday afternoon that Estrada has instructed Foreign Secretary
Domingo Siazon to inform the Bureau of International Exposition
(BIE) that his decision to relinquish the country's right to host
the global fair is final.
</P>
<P>
"He instructed Secretary Siazon to immediately convey the
Philippines' decision to concerned parties so that other
countries, which bid for the hosting of the event, could make
their final preparations and arrangement with the BIE," Barican
said.
</P>
<P>
Barican said that Estrada gave the order after the private
sector "failed to come up with the needed financial package and
cash requirements for the hosting of World Expo 2002."
</P>
<P>
Estrada earlier said he would reconsider his decision to
withdraw the country's hosting bid if the private sector could
raise the 6 billion pesos (150 million U.S. dollars) needed to
stage the event.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government would not spend a single centavo of
public funds for the project due to budgetary constraints.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
