<HEADLINE> IMF Boss Postpones Trip to Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Director of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF), Michel Camdessus, has postponed his planned
trip to Nigeria due to Brazil's financial turmoil, local media
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus was expected to be in Nigeria from January 19 to 22,
during which he was scheduled to meet with Nigerian leader
Abdulsalam Abubakar and Finance Minister Malam Ismaila Usman on
key economic issues.
</P>
<P>
But a spokesman of the IMF said Sunday in Washington that
Camdessus had to postpone the trip because of the financial
turmoil in Brazil. He said no new date has been fixed.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has been negotiating with the IMF for a possible relief
of its external debt, which is estimated to be 20 billion U.S.
Dollars by itself but put at 28 billion Dollars by the IMF.
