<HEADLINE> Tanzania Warns Refugees against Firearms, Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has warned all
the refugees sheltered on its territories against possessing
firearms illegally and committing crimes, local newspapers
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The reports said Tanzanian Minister for Home Affairs Ali Ameir
Mohamed has ordered refugees who possess firearms illegally to
surrender them to relevant authorities during his three-day visit
in the western Kigoma region over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
He told the refugees at the camps that they must refrain from
taking part in banditry or they will meet punitive measures.
</P>
<P>
"Any military activities by refugees might cause military
clashes between Tanzania and her neighboring countries, something
unhealthy for two friendly countries," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Last year Tanzanian parliament passed a bill, limiting the free
travel by refugees outside their camps.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed requested the services like health, water and education
by relief organizations to refugees which are also offered to the
Tanzanians who have been living with refugees peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at least 5,400 new Rwandan refugees entered
neighboring Kagera Region last week to flee fresh fighting between
the government troops and rebels of the late Rwandan President
Juvenali Habyarimana, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
They quoted refugees as saying that Rwandan soldiers have
launched an operation to arrest all Interahamwe militia who are
alleged to have taken part in the 1994 Rwanda massacres over some
500,000 people, mainly Tutsis and moderate Hutus.
</P>
<P>
So far, it is estimated that over 350,000 refugees from
Burundi, the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), Rwanda and
Somalia are in refugee camps in Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
