<HEADLINE> Share Prices Up on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Share prices ran up on the
Singapore Stock Market Monday as foreign investors pushed up large
capitalized stocks.
</P>
<P>
The run-up came after Wall Street rebounded last week and fear
of a financial meltdown in Brazil eased.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) surged up 47.29 points
to close at 1,547.10 points.
</P>
<P>
The total volume thinned to 334.07 million units worth 610.50
million Singapore dollars (362.85 million U.S. dollars). Losers
edged out gainers by 166 to 137 with 119 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
CPH topped the actives chart of the day with a turnover of
40.19 million units. SembCorp was the second most-heavily traded
share with a turnover of 22.29 million units. Poh Lian was next
with 20.08 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
DBS F was the most favorite stock of the day soaring up 130
cents to end at 15.00 Singapore dollars. It was followed by
Creative 50 that surged up 120 cents to close at 26.70 Singapore
dollars. OCBC F ran up 100 cents to close at 13.50 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, AV Jenn led the descents of the day shedding
17 cents to close at 0.47 Australian dollar. SemMar-Log retreated
eight cents to 3.06 Singapore dollars. CSA sank 25 cents to end at
1.05 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said Wall Street's strong close on Friday was a signal
that global stock markets relaxed a little after Brazil had taken
a move to float its currency in stride.
</P>
<P>
They also said institutional players expected the Brazil crisis
will not have a significant impact on the region and returned to
the market, making banks' stocks snapped up.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, retail players located in profits after last week's
run-up on small stocks, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
