<HEADLINE> China Life Reports Sharp Increase in Premiums </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China Life Insurance Company
announced today that its 1988 premium income hit 53 billion yuan,
up 34.3 percent on the previous year.
</P>
<P>
China Life spokesman Wang Yaohua said the company paid victims
of natural disasters and various accidents over four billion yuan
in compensation in recent year, with the volume of paid-up
insurance totaling 15 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
"The company has played a special role in promoting social
stability and ensuring the ability of policyholders to lead
normal lives," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
He added that China Life, a commercial life insurance
enterprise, minimized operating risks during 1998, he said,
adding that the company recovered bad debts of over 260 million
yuan and substantially reduced capital losses last year.
</P>
<P>
It also improved returns with bond purchases of some 20
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China Life's premium target for 1999 has been set at 50 billion
yuan, and the company plans to adopt effective measures to
further reduce operating costs, gradually cut non-performing
assets and improve efficiency, according to Wang.  
</P>
