<HEADLINE> Offshore Oil Sector to Increase Profitability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The China National Offshore
Oil Corp. (CNOOC) plans to cut production cost this year in a bid
to raise profits to one billion yuan in spite of declining oil
prices and markets worldwide, according to a senior official tod
ay.
</P>
<P>
CNOOC President Wei Liucheng said the corporation plans to
produce 15.5 million tons of crude oil and 3.8 billion cu.m. of
natural gas during the year.
</P>
<P>
Wei noted that China's oil industry weathered the severe tests
of the Asian financial crisis, as well as declining prices and
markets, and rampant smuggling in 1998.
</P>
<P>
China successfully reshaped its petroleum system and the CNOOC
succeeded in fulfilling government production targets by
dramatically cutting production costs and expanding oil and gas
exploration and production.
</P>
<P>
Statistics shows that CNOOC produced 16.31 million tons of
crude oil and 3.8 billion cu.m. of natural gas in 1998. Verified
oil and gas reserves grew by 172 million tons and 5.8 billion
cu.m. by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Wei said the CNOOC will prioritize offshore oil and gas
exploration during 1999, and will attempt to attract wide-ranging
foreign cooperation in oil and gas exploration in the South China
Sea, East China Sea and Yellow Sea. 
</P>
