<HEADLINE> Back Problem Forces Rios Out of Australian Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rios, the Open runner-up last year, told organizers he had a
stress fracture in his back which he aggravated playing in New
Zealand last week.
</P>
<P>
The Chilean world No. 2 underwent an MRI scan and was advised
to rest until March.
</P>
<P>
Rios was the third high profile male player to pull out of the
tournament before striking a ball and left organizers, who two
weeks ago boasted a full list of the top 20 men in the world,
with a tournament with gaping holes.
</P>
<P>
World No. 1 Pete Sampras withdrew earlier in the month citing
exhaustion brought on by a hectic end to 1998, and 11th seed
Goran Ivanisevic pulled out today, also with back trouble.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawals reflected the heavy physical pressure the
world's elite tennis players are under and, as devastating as
they were to organizers, they came as no surprise.
</P>
<P>
The problems troubling both Rios and Ivanisevic emerged before
the open began on Monday, but both players had hoped they would
be fit to play.
</P>
<P>
Rios had forfeited midway through his first round match in
Auckland last week and Ivanisevic dropped out after playing only
one match at the Colonial Classic in Melbourne at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Rios was to have begun play on Tuesday with a first-round
match against Italian Gianluca Pozzi and he was replaced by
Spaniard Oscar Serrano.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, German Anke Huber upset 13th seed Romanian Irina
Spirlea 7-5, 6-4 during the first round on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a narrow victory, American Venus Williams beat Croatian 84
ranked Silvija Talaja 3-6, 6-3, 9-7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
