<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysians Urged to Strive to Revive Economic Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Monday called upon his countrymen to strive
harder to revive all economic activities in the country.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir commended Malaysians for being highly disciplined and
patient in facing the economic slowdown and not panicking or
losing their sense of direction but working hard to increase the
national income and revive the economy.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that if all citizens are of one heart and purpose,
our country will return to its original strong economic position
within a short period," he said in his message marking the Eid
al-Fitr, the end of the holy month of Ramadan, over radio and
television Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysians generally stood solidly behind the
government and this had foiled efforts by certain groups to
destroy the Malaysian economy and force the country to bow to
their demands.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that the economic problems would abate
by the turn of the century, saying there was an increased
possibility now of overcoming these woes as the government had
succeeded in freeing the national economy from the pressures of
currency traders and foreign share speculators.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance of Muslims in Malaysia preserving
peace and order in the country, Mahathir said "For if there are
racial riots in Malaysia, Muslims also will become victims and may
become weak and be controlled by others."
</P>
<P>
He also urged Malaysians to cooperate with one another for
their mutual progress and not damage the country through the
pursuit of self interest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
