<HEADLINE> Asian Visitors to Australia Continue to Decrease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The number of visitors to
Australia from Asia continued to fall, with that of South Korean
visitors dipping by nearly three-quarters last October compared
with October, 1997.
</P>
<P>
A bulletin issued by the Australian Bureau of Statistics Monday
showed that the number of visitors from northeast Asia last
October fell by almost a quarter (22.0 percent) to 86,000, while
the number of Southeast Asian arrivals fell by 17.3 percent to
42,000.
</P>
<P>
South Korean visitors led the fall in the arrivals from
northeast Asia, with a dramatic drop of 72.6 percent to just
6,000.
</P>
<P>
The most significant decline in Southeast Asian visitor
arrivals was recorded from Malaysia and Indonesia - down 33.3
percent to 8,200 and 24.1 percent to 8,200 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the total number of visitors to Australia fell a
marginal 3.2 percent to 354,800 last October from October 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
