<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 09:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Bans Overseas Phone Calls Via Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Post and
Telecommunications of Lebanon has banned Internet service
providers from offering voice communications service, the Daily
Star reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The service, known as the Voice Over the Internet, provides
Internet subscribers with a cheap means of calling overseas.
</P>
<P>
Internet service providers will be prosecuted if they fail to
comply with the terms and regulations of their licenses, warned
Abdel Monem Youssef, general director of the ministry's operations
and maintainance section.
</P>
<P>
The licenses, which were granted by the ministry, require
Internet companies to refrain from offering voice services. And
video conferencing is also banned.
</P>
<P>
Only the ministry has the exclusive right to provide
international and local phone lines, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
And Internet companies which don't abide by the terms of their
licenses are undermining the ministry's revenues and depleting
public funds, Youssef said.
</P>
<P>
Following the ministry's decision Saturday, Intracom, one of
the several companies that offer what is called the "e-phone
service", announced to suspend its phone-via-Internet service.
</P>
<P>
The company had launched a nation-wide advertising campaign a
week ago to promote the new product.
</P>
<P>
Of Lebanon's 10 Internet service providers in operation, only
four have access lines spread throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The service providers are generating approximately 1 million
U.S. dollars a month in revenues, thanks to growing numbers of
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the ministry show that Lebanon has less than
half of the Arab world's 85,000 Internet subscribers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Develop Disaster Preparedness Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China has planned to
accelerate the development of earthquake forcasting centers.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Seismological Bureau is currently evaluating
related projects and drafting a national plan for development of
the industry.
</P>
<P>
"Introducing high technology and establishing a domestic
disaster preparedness research system will reduce damage
resulting from earthquakes," according to Lu Deshou,
vice-director of the bureau's disaster preparedness department.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that development of the new industry will involve
wide-ranging sectors, including the electronics, machine-building
and new materials industries.
</P>
<P>
China's accuracy rate for earthquake predicitons has reached
advanced international levels following a three-decade effort by
scientists. However, the accuracy rate for short-term predictions
of earthquakes within three days is lower than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the lack of timely predictions for earthquakes has
resulted in the loss of many lives, said Lu, adding that the
large number of fatalities during the Tangshan earthquake in 1967
was the direct result of the lack of timely predictions.
(
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
