<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The international community has expressed indignation over
the massacre of 45 ethnic Albanians by Serb forces in Kosovo. The
prosecutor of the International Criminal Tribunal in the Hague,
Louise Arbour, has expressed the hope to investigate the killings
in the field and launch judicial inquiry against those held
responsible for crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
-- West African countries are disputing over how to
re-establish peace and constitutional legality in Sierra Leone as
Nigeria has expressed opposition to the mediation by Cote
d'Ivoire and Togo. Nigeria, which has sent 15,000 peacekeeping
forces to Sierra Leone, said one cannot negotiate with the rebels
of United Revolution Front which massacres civilians.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- With the massacre of 45 Albanian civilians in Kosovo,
Belgrade has chosen the worst policy in the conflict in the
province. The international community has strongly reacted to the
killings and U.S. Ambassador William Walker, who is chief of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe in Kosovo,
has described it as a "crime against humanity".
</P>
<P>
-- After announcing the abandoning of nuclear stations, German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder is facing defiance within his own
Social-Democratic Party. The minister-presidents of
Rhenania-Westphalia and Lower-Saxony are rejecting plans to
repatriate nuclear wastes to their lands from the stocking center
in la Hague, France. 
</P>
