<HEADLINE> Arab Leaders to Welcome King Hussein's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Some Arab leaders are expected to
join a grand welcome ceremony Tuesday for Jordanian King Hussein's
return to the kingdom from a six-month cancer treatment in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
However, the official list of those high-ranking Arab visitors
is not available yet.
</P>
<P>
It has been confirmed that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa al-Thani will attend the
event, the national daily Jordan Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the ceremony will be the United Arab Emirates
Chief of Staff Sheikh Mohammed Bin Zayed and other high-ranking
officials from Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Some Arab heads of state have also voiced their desire to visit
King Hussein, including Saudi Arabian Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn
Abdul-Aziz and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
More than 1 million Jordanians are to take to the streets to
celebrate King Hussein's homecoming.
</P>
<P>
Hussein left Jordan for the United States in mid-July 1998 and
underwent treatment for lymphatic cancer.
</P>
<P>
Hussein has said on several occasions that he had fully
recovered from his illness after treatment at the Mayo Clinic,
Minnesota in the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The king had stayed in Washington and London for more than two
weeks for recuperation after he left the Mayo Clinic last
December. 
</P>
