<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sword Adds Clues to Western Han Culture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A bronze sword dating to the
Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C.--24 A.D.) has been found in Puding
County in southwest China's Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
This is the maiden finding of such a relic in the southwestern
part, making people know more about the country's culture over
the period.
</P>
<P>
The sword is queerly shaped, with a gourd-like hilt and a long
sunken part, with a length of 29.6 centimeters.
</P>
<P>
A farmer at Huachu Village found the sword when digging a well
in front of his house.
</P>
<P>
The sword-lying part was a mountain valley, and then became
arable land after many years of alluviation, archeologists say,
ruling out the possibility for the sword to come from a tomb or
an ancient relic site.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Overhaul Tariff System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is expected to
streamline its tariff system in the next several months to better
support development of industry, agriculture and the environment.
</P>
<P>
The overhaul, the first since 1995, will give some relief to
importers affected by the weakened baht and shrinking local
markets, finance ministry officials said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The changes will affect abut 7,000 product categories. The
maximum tariff on the majority of products is 30 percent, with
some officials saying they favor a cap of between 15 percent and
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Reductions of rates on many products would help reduce
production costs for industries dependent on imported raw
materials and intermediate products.
</P>
<P>
Lower import tariffs would also increase pressure on domestic
producers to cut their own costs and improve quality, a crucial
medium-term goal for policy makers looking ahead to increased
competition from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Still, sensitive industries such as agriculture would continue
to be protected under the tariff regime, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda has told members of a
tariff study group to submit their findings by mid-year. The
group, chaired by finance ministry permanent secretary Supachai
Pisitvanich, includes representatives of the Board of Investment
and the industry, commerce and agriculture ministers.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural and environmental products were left largely
untouched in the 1995 tariff overhaul. But both categories,
particularly agricultural goods, will be evaluated closely.
Tariffs on agricultural products now are as high as 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Another industry likely to be affected is petrochemicals. Tens
of billions of baht has been invested in building up a domestic
petrochemical industry that remains uncompetitive despite generous
tariff protection.
</P>
<P>
One challenge will be balancing the local demands of upstream
petrochemical producers for protection from imports, against calls
by intermediate and downstream companies for lower tariffs to
reduce production costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
