<HEADLINE> Britain Deploys Warship off Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
deployed a navy frigate in the troubled waters off Sierra Leone to
assist in the monitoring of rebel activities in that country,
media reports said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The frigate of HMS Norfolk with a detachment of troops and a
Lynx helicopter on board was sent to the west African country when
the rebels invaded central and eastern areas of capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of the warship off Freetown was aimed at
providing " logistical" support to the west African peacekeeping
force known as ECOMOG which is supporting the
democratically-elected President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, according to
British officials.
</P>
<P>
But, the heavily-armed warship and its crew will not take a
direct part in fighting between the ECOMOG troops and the rebels,
they said.
</P>
<P>
Omrie Golley, spokesman of the rebel Revolutionary United Front
(RUF), said Sunday in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, that RUF commanders
in the field feared that the Norfolk planned to guide ECOMOG's
Alpha jet warplanes.
</P>
<P>
"They are worried it will eavesdrop on our communications and
help the Alphas pinpoint our positions," he added.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the deployment of warship was in response to the
calls made last week by the Commonwealth Secretary-General Emeka
Anyaoku on the international community to support Nigeria's
efforts in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Britain flew in a transport plane full of military jeeps for
ECOMOG on Friday, according to a spokesman for the ECOMOG force.
</P>
<P>
In a statement last week, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook
announced an extra aid of one million Pounds to the ECOMOG forces
in Freetown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
