<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Power Revenue Up in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Uganda Electricity Board's
(UEB) revenue from the supply of power to local customers grossed
81.9 billion Shillings (81.9 million U.S. Dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Monday's Monitor newspaper quoted a senior official with the
UEB as saying over the weekend that this figure represents an
increase of 33 percent from that of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Revenue from the export of power to Kenya, Tanzania and Rwanda
went up by 15 percent to a level of 14.4 billion Shillings (14.4
million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The parastatal's total revenue from electricity bills had
dramatically gone up from 67 percent a few years ago to over 85
percent in 1998, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, UEB is still losing about 24 percent of its revenue to
unbilled consumers.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is a country which is suffering from lack of power. The
Owen Falls Dam, which has a capacity of 180 megawatts a year,
satisfies three quarters of the country's total power demand.
</P>
<P>
Due to the current economic growth in Uganda, power demand has
already outstripped supply. The power deficit has resulted in
frequent load- shedding through which various parts of the country
are switched off from supply at peak hours of the day.
</P>
<P>
The inadequate electricity supply and frequent power cuts have
adversely affected economic activities and industries are
operating at 37 percent under capacity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
