<HEADLINE> Listing of China Bonds Helps to Deepen HK Debt Market: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) Tung Chee Hwa said here
Monday that the listing of China bonds in Hong Kong represented a
big step forward for the local debt market.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks here Monday during a meeting with China's
Minister of Finance Xiang Huaicheng, who came to attend the
signing ceremony for the listing of China bonds on the Hong Kong
Stock Exchange. The Ministry of Finance of the People's Republic
of China successfully issued one billion U.S. dollar global bonds
in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
Tung said: "I welcome the listing in Hong Kong of the bonds
issued by the Ministry of Finance as this would help to deepen
and broaden our debt market. It represents a big step forward for
our debt market."
</P>
<P>
Statistics provided by the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA)
show that the gross value of all debt products in Hong Kong by
the end of August 1998 amounted to 390.7 billion HK dollars (50
billion U.S. dollars), of which 17 percent were Exchange Fund
Bills and Notes issued by the HKMA.
</P>
<P>
Tung noted that apart from the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, the
Hong Kong Stock Exchange is the only place of listing for the
U.S. dollar bonds issued by China's Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
"The listing here of the bonds also enhanced Hong Kong's role
as China's fund raising center," said the Chief Executive.
</P>
<P>
Tung and Xiang also exchanged views on the global and regional
economic development and recent performance of the international
financial market.
</P>
<P>
Before he met Tung, the finance minister paid a visit to the
Stock Exchange of Hong Kong on Monday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
