<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Cut Steel Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China plans to cut its steel
output to eliminate overproduction, according to Wang Wanbin,
director of the State Administration of Metallurgical Industrial.
</P>
<P>
Wang made the comment during today's national metallurgical i
ndustry meeting. He said this year's profit target of five
billion yuan (602.4 million US dollars) is based on strictly
controlling gross output. Efforts will also center on preventing
46 medium- to large-sized steel producers from incurring losses.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show China increased pig iron output by 6.7
percent to 118 million tons during 1998, with steel output rising
by 6.9 percent to 114 million tons and rolled steel output by 9.8
percent to 105 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The total 1998 output value for the metallurgical sector hit
195 billion yuan, a year-on-year rise of 5.4 percent. The
sector's profits for the year stood at some two billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Wang said overproduction has resulted in the excessive waste
of resources, and warned that measures must be adopted to prevent
huge losses of state assets.
</P>
<P>
China's steel output has jumped substantially since 1993, with
the 1998 output alone growing by 24.5 million tons, or 27.4
percent. However, 1998 profits fell to 2.3 billion yuan last
year, compared to a high of 29.4 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Wang attributed the drop to normal price cuts, as well as
overproduction resulting from redundant construction.
</P>
<P>
He said the goal of controlling production is to increase
returns for steel producers and create conditions for
technological advances and the development of sound enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
