<HEADLINE> Israel's Labor Legislator to Join Centrist Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A veteran politician of
Israel's opposition Labor Party will formally leave the party and
join the centrist party which was set up by Amnon Lipkin-Shahak,
former chief of staff of Israeli military.
</P>
<P>
Nissim Zvilli, who is also a member of Israeli Knesset
(parliament), told local daily The Jerusalem Post on Sunday night
that he left the Labor because he did not think it would win the
elections scheduled on May.
</P>
<P>
"I don't believe (Labor leader Ehud) Barak stands a chance of
defeating (Prime Minister Benjamin) Netanyahu in the Elections,"
said Zvilli.
</P>
<P>
Zvilli also predicted that Shahak would be elected as prime
minister since "someone with his nature can ease the atmosphere
currently pervading the country."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Knesset finally approved early this month a bill
calling for early elections and all main parties have launched
their election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zeev Begin, son of former prime minister Menachem
Begin, registered his right-wing party Herut on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The party's key guiding principles include increasing Jewish
settlements throughout "Israel and the Land of Israel" and not
handing over Golan Heights to any foreign regime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
