<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review on China's Foreign Trade (Jan 11-17) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Following are the main foreign
trade events in China between January 11 and 17:
</P>
<P>
-- Monday, Exports in 1998 Slightly up:
</P>
<P>
China's General Administration of Customs released on Monday
that overall export volume in 1998 rose 0.5 percent from a year
ago to reach 183.76 billion U.S. dollars while imports going down
1.5 percent to 140.17 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign trade volume went down for the first time since
1983 last year to 323.93 billion U.S. dollars. It was 0.4 percent
down from 1997.
</P>
<P>
-- Wednesday, Further Investment From Siemens
</P>
<P>
Visiting Siemens Chairman and CEO Heinrich Von Pierer said on
Wednesday his company will increase its investments in China by
one billion German marks over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
He said future investment will mainly go to infrastructures,
especially the transportation sector.
</P>
<P>
He said Siemens will not establish many joint-ventures, but
will focus on developing existing businesses.
</P>
<P>
However, Siemens is expected to invest 35 million German marks
to establish a joint venture on electronic auto components in
Zhuzhou in central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
-- Wednesday, Sino-Portuguese MCCT Held:
</P>
<P>
The 4th meeting of the Sino-Portuguese Mixed Committee on
Commerce and Trade was held in Beijing on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Shi Guangsheng, China's minister of foreign trade and economic
cooperation, and his Portuguese counterpart Joaquim Pina Moura
agreed that there will be concrete measures to increase trade
relations and economic cooperation between their two countries.
</P>
<P>
Shi said his ministry will organized a trip of Chinese
business people to Portugal this year to learn more about the
country and seek opportunities for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
-- Thursday, Wu Yi Meets Portuguese Trade Minister
</P>
<P>
Chinese State Councilor Wu Yi met Portuguese Trade Minister
Joaquim Pina Moura on Thursday. They discussed trade cooperation,
the return of Macao to China and China's entry into the World
Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
-- Saturday, Firm Stance To Join WTO
</P>
<P>
A seminar on the World Trade Organization opened on Saturday.
Long Yongtu, the chief negotiator of China's Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), attended the seminar and
said that China will continue to make an effort to join the WTO.
</P>
<P>
As long as China continues its policy of opening to the
outside world and is determined to build its socialist market
economy, efforts to join the WTO will not cease and negotiations
will continue, he said.
</P>
<P>
China must be determined in its policy of opening to the
outside world, he said, because China needs to keep up with the
globalization of the world economy. 
