<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Release Tests of Y2K for Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines will release at the end of March the official results
of the validation tests its examiners conducted on the computer
system efficiency of banks in order to remedy the effects of the
millennium bug problems in the country.
</P>
<P>
In an interview here Monday, Dolores Yuvienco, head of the
central bank's Y2K Task Force, said that there is no need to worry
about the problem because the central bank is doing everything to
address the problem before the year 2000, when all computer
systems will read the last two zeros in computers as 1900.
</P>
<P>
She urged banks to complete all the testing of internal and
external systems by June 1999.
</P>
<P>
The central bank issued a circular in September 1997 requiring
banks to submit action plans for conversion program for the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
In June 1998, the central bank issued another circular which
required them to accomplish a self-assessment questionnaire in
order to determine the quality of their preparation.
</P>
<P>
Yuvienco said that those who will fail to submit a monthly
report of their actions as mandated in the two circulars will be
subjected to certain enforcement actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
