<HEADLINE> Kaunda Not to Give Up Power: Zambian Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- President of Zambia's
opposition party, the United National Independence Party (UNIP),
Kenneth Kaunda, will never relinquish party leadership until the
party returns to power, its administrative secretary Basil Kabwe
has said.
</P>
<P>
"In the leadership of the UNIP, members throughout the country
have told Kaunda in no uncertain terms, that congress or no
congress, they will never let him go until UNIP gets back into
power," Kabwe said.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail Monday quoted Kabwe as saying "anyone who
thinks that a new leader can replace Kaunda and expect to lead the
UNIP to victory in 2001, is a victim of wishful thinking and pipe
dreaming".
</P>
<P>
He also said the party performed badly in the recent local
government elections because internal strife, wrangling and
character assassination have continued unabated within the Central
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The internal strife has made it difficult for leaders to
mobilize members, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kabwe was reacting to press reports attributed to senior Chief
Inyambo Yeta's adviser George Zulu that Kaunda could not lead the
UNIP into the next millennium because he had already played his
role.
</P>
<P>
Kabwe further said it was up to Kaunda himself to say what he
wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda ruled the country for 27 years and was defeated by
incumbent President Frederick Chiluba in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the 74-year old veteran politician told the
British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) in London that he "would
not retire from active politics soon because current events in
Zambia's political arena would not warrant that."
</P>
<P>
Kaunda said he would contest the Zambian presidency in 2001.
And he would continue leading his party until his followers decide
he had to leave. 
</P>
</TEXT>
