<HEADLINE> Agreement Inked on Listing of China Bonds in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Finance
and the Hong Kong Stock Exchange signed an agreement here Monday
for the listing of China global bonds issued at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government successfully issued one billion U.S.
dollar Global Bond in December 1998, the first time that China
re-entered the international capital market as a sovereign issuer
since the outbreak of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Xiang Huaicheng, China's Minister of Finance, said at the
signing ceremony Monday: "We strongly support Hong Kong in her
efforts to develop a full-fledged bond market, and to maintain
her importance as one of the world's financial centers. "
</P>
<P>
"The decision by the Ministry of Finance of the People's
Republic of China to list the Global Bond in the Hong Kong Stock
Exchange and myself being here today at this listing signing
ceremony, are to help achieve this objective," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Guangyao, Director General, International Department of
the Ministry of Finance, and Alec Tsui, Chief Executive of the
Hong Kong Stock Exchange, inked the listing agreement, which
replaced one signed in 1993 and incorporated several minor
technical updates.
</P>
<P>
Donald Tsang, Financial Secretary of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), said on the same occasion: "I deeply
believe that the bonds issued by the Ministry of Finance will
soon develop as another successful product in the Hong Kong
market."
</P>
<P>
He stressed: "The signing ceremony represented that Hong
Kong's securities market has entered into a new era, it also
symbolized that our role as China's fund raising center has been
further enhanced."
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, there have been seven issues of Chinese bonds on
the Hong Kong bourse, including the latest one billion U.S. doll
ar China Global Bond due in 2008.
</P>
<P>
The SAR's Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa Monday attended the
signing ceremony and proposed a toast to the successful
development of the Hong Kong debt market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
