<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya, Uganda Target Anti-Malaria Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan manufacturer of an
over-the- counter anti-malaria treatment banned by Uganda recently
has defended the quality of its product, Dawaquin, which remains
on sale elsewhere in east Africa.
</P>
<P>
Rogers Atebe, chief pharmacist of Dawa Pharmaceuticals which is
the Nairobi manufacturer of the drug banned three weeks ago by
Uganda's National Drug Authority (NDA), said Dawaquin is
manufactured to stringent quality standards and could therefore
not be substandard.
</P>
<P>
The chloroquine-based drug may be taken for both curative and
prophylactic purposes in the event of malaria, he was quoted by
Monday's East African weekly as saying.
</P>
<P>
Uganda ordered the drug's withdrawal, saying tests by the NDA
found it did not contain the recommended levels of chloroquine.
The NDA is Uganda's overall drugs registration and regulatory
body.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, Beth Rapuoda, the head of country's malaria control
 program, said although she did not have specific data on
Dawaquin, the program's policy was that such chloroquine-based
anti-malaria should be gradually withdrawn as resistance levels to
them had reached unacceptable levels. Dawaquin, however, is still
on sale in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Since last November, Rapuoda said, Kenya had adopted new
guidelines on the treatment of malaria, replacing chloroquine with
sulphadoxin / pyrimethamine as the first line treatment for
malaria. The guidelines will be implemented in Kenyan public
hospitals this year.
</P>
<P>
Dawaquin's ban in Uganda was announced in the wake of a report
in the December issue of the East African Medical Journal that
more than half of all chloroquine-based anti-malaria drugs on sale
in Uganda were substandard.
</P>
<P>
The study involved testing chloroquine phosphate tablets and
injectable samples obtained from 50 registered pharmacies and drug
dealers selected at random in Kampala.
</P>
<P>
The samples obtained were manufactured in India, Kenya, Uganda,
Europe, China, Cuba and Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
