<HEADLINE> Rebels in DRC Can Only Meet Kabila in Kisangani: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of rebels
fighting to oust President Laurent Kabila of the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) can only hold direct talks with him in
Kisangani, one of their bases in the east, a rebel leader has
said.
</P>
<P>
Rebel chief leader Earnest Wamba dia Wamba made the
announcement on Sunday, according to a report in Monday's New
Vision newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Wamba was quoted as saying that his offer of Kisangani as a
venue to meet the government side was to counter the offer by
Kabila to meet them in the capital city Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
On January 7, Kabila made a surprise offer on state television
to meet the rebels in Kinshasa, stressing that there was no
question of their going to meet the rebels elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Face-to-face negotiation has always been the rebels' main
precondition to discuss any possible ceasefire, Wamba said.
</P>
<P>
With military support from Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia, Chad and
others, Kabila had refused to talk to the rebels, who occupy
nearly half of the country, before making the offer on television.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rebels, though allegedly supported by Uganda and
Rwanda, have difficulty in gaining new ground on the front line.
</P>
<P>
The stalemate and the prolonging of the five-month-long war has
drawn regional and international attention. But no peaceful
solution to the problem is yet in sight since neither of the two
sides agree to make concessions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
