<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Initiates Policy Research on Population Aging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's population of over 13
million people includes 320 centenarians, up 30 percent on last
year's figure.
</P>
<P>
Three Shanghainese have reached the age of 109, with the list
of centenarians including one couple living in suburban district,
according to a report carried today in a Shanghai-based newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The report demonstrated the nationwide concern about the
rising number of senior citizens in China, the world's most
populous country which is currently facing a so-called "graying
tide".
</P>
<P>
China will have 400 million people over the age of 60 within a
short 50 years, compared to the current total on 120 million,
according to estimates released by the China National Committee
on Aging (CNCA) which studies aging issues.
</P>
<P>
Major cities such as Shanghai and Beijing have witnessed
rapidly rising aging populations in recent years, with close to
10 percent their citizens over the age of 60.
</P>
<P>
One CNCA official noted that solutions must be found for a
number of problems related to aging, including social welfare and
insurance services for senior citizens, and effectively
protecting their rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
The CNCA has launched a comprehensive project to formulate
national policy research on aging issued in the first half of
next century.
</P>
<P>
"Lawmakers must be prepared to face new challenges related to
aging," according to CNCA Chairman Zhang Wenfan. He added that
related efforts will require extensive advice and scientific
research.
</P>
<P>
Scholars plans to focus on subjects such as the impact aging
will have on China's economy and society, as well as policies for
senior citizens and longevity research.
</P>
<P>
A nationwide survey on the aging population in urban districts
will be undertaken to support the project, said Zhang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
