<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Use English as State Language, Scrapping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda has decided to replace
French with English as its official language, Rwanda President
Pasteur Bizimungu announced on the eve of the East African
Cooperation (EAC) summit slated for January 21 which will discuss
Rwanda's membership application.
</P>
<P>
The regional organization groups three English-speaking
countries -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu was quoted by Monday's East African weekly as saying
that because Rwanda's historical, cultural and business links with
east Africa are stronger than those shared with faraway
French-speaking west African countries, Rwandans are already
hoping to join the EAC.
</P>
<P>
He said Rwanda will now align itself with the Anglophone
nations of east Africa instead of its traditional Francophone
partners because France played a role in the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
"If you follow the recent reports of investigations from the
French parliament, it is clearly indicated that France has been
involved in the genocide in Rwanda and in the events which
preceded the massacres, because they wanted to defend their own
language," said the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
