<HEADLINE> Manila Vows to Pursue Peace Talks With Rebel Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Monday that it is determined to pursue peace negotiations with the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) despite the rebel group's
attacks on government troops in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview here Monday, Executive Secretary Ronaldo
Zamora said that the government's peacekeeping forces are ready to
launch offensives against lawless elements as a way to restore
peace and order in Mindanao, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The government is aware that the attacks on government
detachments are the handiwork of the MILF and not of its lost
commands, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue peace negotiations with the MILF, but we will
not allow them to talk peace and attack us at the same time, then
point the blame to lost commands, we don't believe that. We know
that they are under one central command. We want to make sure they
understand that," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said this was the reason President Joseph Estrada
ordered the police and military to step up their offensives
against criminality and terrorism in Mindanao as early as two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The 12,000-strong MILF is fighting for an independent Islamic
state in the Southern Philippines, but its demand has been
rejected by the government. The two sides are scheduled to start
formal peace talks in the first week of February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
