<HEADLINE> Philippines to Address Unemployment Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
convene a National Conference on Labor and Employment here
Thursday to tackle the unemployment issue.
</P>
<P>
According to Labor Secretary Bienvendio Laguesma, the
conference will pave the way for a new national employment agenda
geared to substantially improve the job situation this year and
for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The conference will be attended by top government officials,
heads of the tripartite social-partner organizations, leaders of
non-government organizations and the basic sectors, he said in a
report released Monday.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada, Senate President Marcelo Fernan,
House Speaker Manuel Villar and Laguesma will deliver speeches at
the meeting, followed by sectoral statements from the organized
labor, employers and the basic sectors, the secretary said.
</P>
<P>
Laguesma said in holding the conference, the government is
trying to provide support, security, and an environment conducive
to the uplift of the poor.
</P>
<P>
"Job security, in particular, is important in view of the
continuing effects of the Asian crisis and the most probable
recurrence of the El Nino and La Nina phenomena during the next
medium-term," the labor chief said.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that the country's unemployment rate has
climbed to 13 percent from 9 percent since the financial crisis
started 19 months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
