<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5,000-Year-Old Cultural Relics Damaged in Shaanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Shizuitou cultural relics site in Baoji City, about 180
kilometers west of Xi'an, capital of the province, has been under
preservation at the provincial level since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The relics include rich cultural ruins dating back to the New
Stone Age and the Qin (221-207 B.C.) and Han (206 B.C.-220 A.D.)
dynasties. A Xinhua reporter saw a 20-meter-deep ditch, hundreds
of meters long and dozens of meters wide, which had been dug out
at the Shizuitou cultural relics site, which covers an area of
20,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The damaged relics include pottery of the New Stone Age, house
ruins of the Longshan Culture dating back 4,000-4,500 years,
bricks of the Han Dynasty and ruins of the ancient pottery kiln
as well as three tombs.
</P>
<P>
Police in Baoji City also confiscated a large number of
cultural relics illegally held by some construction workers,
including pottery bowls belonging to the New Stone Age and the
Zhou Dynasty, and knives, swords, jade hairpins and more than 200
coins of the Han Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
As early as May 1996, Baoji City's archeological team had
submitted a map outlining the cultural relics site to the
construction company.
</P>
<P>
However, the request to pay attention and protect the relics
during construction, which began last November, was ignored.
</P>
<P>
The city's cultural relics protection department is said to
take legal actions against the construction unit, accusing it of
violating the state Cultural Relics Protection Law which
stipulates that construction projects are forbidden on cultural
relics sites under protection.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi in northwest china is well-known for its numerous
cultural relics and historical sites. The Shizuitou site attracts
great many tourists from home and abroad every year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
