<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Railways Raises Freight Charges to Inland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Railways Corporation
(KRC) has announced that it will raise freight charges from the
Indian Ocean port of Mombasa to inland container depots effective
from February 1.
</P>
<P>
Moving a 20-foot container from Mombasa to Kisumu and back --
with the container empty one way -- will now cost 1,016 U.S.
Dollars, up from 800 Dollars, while the charge for a 40-foot
container will be 1,575 Dollars, up from 1,500 Dollars, the East
African weekly reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Charges for the same trip, but with the container loaded both
ways, will be 886 Dollars, up from 844 Dollars, for a 20-foot
container, according to the special traffic notice released by the
corporation.
</P>
<P>
The changes come exactly one year after Kenya Railways effected
a 10- percent hike in freight charges, citing increased demand for
Railtainer services following extensive damage to the country's
road and railways systems by the El Nino rains. No reasons were
given for this year's price hikes.
</P>
<P>
Last year's increase in tariffs provoked protests from
shipping agents and clearing and forwarding firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
