<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Puts Politics on Net </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Only five days after the State Development Planning Commission
launched its website on December 1, 1998, a total of 1,400
visitors had posted their opinions on the site on topics such as
environmental pollution, anti-corruption and the establishment of
a medical insurance system.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Municipal Government made a recent debut on the
Net with a website called Window of the Capital, which includes
information raging from Beijing's economic situation to job
seeking and air-quality reports.
</P>
<P>
Most significantly, an e-mail box has been open to Beijingers
where they can post letters to the mayor on various issues.
</P>
<P>
The newest statistics show that so far a total of 25,000
citizens have visited this website.
</P>
<P>
The Guangdong provincial government will be connected with the
Hong Kong SAR on May 1, 1999, with its 18 departments already
establishing their sites. Meanwhile the Guangzhou and Shenzhen
city governments have also launched their trial websites.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Chinese government departments have more
than 3,000 databases, making up 80 percent of all social
information resources.
</P>
<P>
"We had taken it for granted that the state development
strategy is a policy-makers' affair, but now we can voice our
suggestions on the Net freely, with a sense of involvement in
state affairs," said one recent visitor to the State Development
Planning Commission's website. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
