<HEADLINE> Philippine, Singapore Navies to Step Up Joint Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and Singapore
have agreed to conduct joint training and exchange of technologies
to bolster the development of their navies.
</P>
<P>
This was the major highlight agreed upon between Vice Admiral
Eduardo Ma. R. Santos, Philippine Navy flag officer in command,
and Rear Admiral Richard Lim Cherng Yih, chief of the Navy of
Singapore, over the weekend, the Philippine News Agency reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Admiral Lim made a three-day official visit to Manila at the
invitation of Admiral Santos.
</P>
<P>
Both Navy chiefs agreed to mutually assist in the fields of
training, transfer of technologies and other expertise, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
It said that Singapore, which has a more advanced Navy in terms
of weaponry, can offer their expertise in the field of
developments of armaments while the Philippines, which has a more
experienced Navy, can extend training skills.
</P>
<P>
The two navies have been exchanging reciprocal visits in the
past few years and conducting joint exercises to hone their skills
in naval exercise. 
