<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Road Crashes Cost NZ 1.7 Billion US Dollars Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The social cost of road
crashes in New Zealand, a country with a population of less than
3.8 million, is estimated at 3.2 billion NZ dollars (1.7 billion
U.S. dollars) a year in hospital treatment, loss of wages,
compensation, counseling and investigation.
</P>
<P>
According to the Land Transport Safety Authority of New
Zealand, 504 people died on New Zealand roads and more than
10,000 were injured last year.
</P>
<P>
The Evening Post Monday quoted Neil Gyde, an officer in charge
of the traffic section of the National Headquarters of the NZ
Police, as saying that police aim to reduce the road toll to 470
deaths and cut reported injuries to 12,400 this year.
</P>
<P>
However, it has been a horror start to 1999 on New Zealand
roads with 27 deaths, the Wellington-based newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
"This year our target is no more than 470 deaths. It's a big
task. We're coming off a baseline of 500-odd," Gyde said.
</P>
<P>
According to the officer, the top three causes of fatalities
are drink-driving, speed and not wearing seatbelts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backlog for Airlines as Wellington Airport Reopens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Airlines have been busy
Monday clearing a backlog of thousands of passengers after the
Wellington International Airport reopened in the morning.
</P>
<P>
The airport was closed to nearly all flights Sunday due to low
cloud and fog.
</P>
<P>
According to local media, Air New Zealand alone canceled 40
domestic and international flights, affecting the travel plans of
at least 3,000 passengers, including many diving teams, who
participated in the 11th Diving World Cup from January 12 to 16.
</P>
<P>
The backlog of passengers is expected to totally clear
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Local media said Wellington air traffic control had problems on
 Saturday morning with a temporary failure of glide path landing
equipment.
</P>
<P>
But Airways Corporation communications manager Heather Hayden
said it could not be used at that time anyway due to low cloud,
which was down to 45m.
</P>
<P>
"The equipment is used to guide pilots when cloud is between
150m and 180m. The failure was unusual and would be investigated,"
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
