<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Inflation Hits 38-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Inflation in New Zealand is
at its lowest point in 38 years, according to figures released by
 Statistics New Zealand Monday.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 the Consumer Price Index (CPI) rose only 0.4 percent,
the smallest annual increase since 1960.
</P>
<P>
In the last quarter of 1998, prices actually fell 0.8 percent,
the largest Quarterly fall since 1957.
</P>
<P>
The main factor pushing prices down was cuts in mortgage rates,
 Statistics New Zealand says, adding banks slashed mortgage rates
to 30-year lows in the latter part of last year, resulting in a
12 percent fall in the mortgage rate component of the CPI.
</P>
<P>
Lower property prices and lower power bills due to increased
competition also pushed the CPI down, according to Statistics New
Zealand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
