<HEADLINE> Commission Proposes Small Enterprise Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Clarifying the property rights
and relationship between administration and enterprises
constitute the core reform for small state-owned firms, according
to a report by the Macroeconomic Research Institute under the
State Development Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Sales of auctions will be used to transform small enterprises
into businesses more suited to the market competition, says the
report by the China Small Enterprise Development Research Panel.
</P>
<P>
The reports notes that the separation of administration from
enterprise management will support anti-corruption and sharpen
competition.
</P>
<P>
Support policies will target the expansion of employment and
anti-poverty efforts, and will promote the specialization and
cooperation and technological renovations.
</P>
<P>
"Achieving related goals will require the further emancipation
of minds and enhanced awareness," according to the report.
</P>
<P>
It urges governments at various levels to attach still greater
attention to supporting the development of small enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Statistics provided by the State Economic and Trade Commission
show that the number of small to medium-sized enterprises account
for 99 percent of ventures in the state-owned industrial sector,
with their output value and pretax profits making up 60 percent
and 40 percent of the respective totals. 
</P>
