<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Draft Law Protecting Private Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China will draft a law to
protect private firms and strengthen regulations on taxation
aimed at such firms, according to a prominent figure in the
nation's legislature.
</P>
<P>
Li Yining, with the National People's Congress (NPC) said here
on Saturday that the Wholly Owned Enterprise Law will be drafted
soon and submitted to the NPC for approval this year.
</P>
<P>
Li, a renowned economist and also deputy director of NPC's
Financial and Economic Committee, has played a key role in the
enactment of the Securities Law passed last month.
</P>
<P>
The Wholly Owned Enterprise Law will mainly focus on
administration and management of private companies owned by
domestic investors, since China already has a law on
overseas-funded businesses, including wholly owned foreign firms,
said Li.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the new law will contain clauses stipulating
standardized accounting management by private firms to prevent
them from evading tax obligations.
</P>
<P>
The law, expected to be promulgated in 1999, will serve as an
initiative taken by China in its efforts to cultivate promising
growth areas for its economy amidst slowing economic growth on
the whole.
</P>
<P>
Official figures showed that output of China's private sector
reached 847 billion yuan (102 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997, and
seven percent of the country's industrial and commercial taxes
were paid by private businesses.
</P>
<P>
As China's state sector is undergoing an overhaul, the country
needs a thriving private sector to absorb workers trimmed from
state firms.
</P>
<P>
However, there is still much discrimination against private
firms as the nation's corporate circles have been dominated by
state enterprises for decades.
</P>
<P>
The country has recently stepped up removing obstacles
hindering development of the private firms.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China, the nation's central bank, began
to permit lending rates of commercial banks to fluctuate in a
wider range around its benchmark rates late last year.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, a group of private companies were allowed to
handle foreign trade on their own for the first time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
