<HEADLINE> Garrett, Jackson to Wolves in Three-Way Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- It will be a homecoming of
sorts for Dean Garret, Bobby Jackson and Chauncey Billups if a
reported three-way trade among the Minnesota Timberwolves, Denver
Nuggets and Toronto Raptors goes through.
</P>
<P>
The Timberwolves would acquire Garrett and Jackson from the
Nuggets. The Wolves would send guard Micheal Williams to the
Raptors, who would ship Billups to Denver.
</P>
<P>
The Raptors would receive at least one first-round draft pick
from the Wolves or Nuggets, who also may receive Raptors forward
Reggie Slater.
</P>
<P>
All deals and signings cannot be announced until Tuesday, when
the NBA is expected to complete the new collective bargaining
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Garrett played for the Timberwolves as a 30-year-old rookie in
the 1996-97 season, averaging 8.0 points and 7.3 rebounds per
game and taking over as the starting center late in the season.
But he left as a free agent to sign a five-year, $15 million
contract with the Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
Jackson, 25, made the All-Rookie Second Team with 11.6 points,
4.7 assists and 4.4 rebounds as a starter last season.
</P>
<P>
Billups was selected third overall by the Boston Celtics last
year. He was dealt to the Raptors in February as part of the
Kenny Anderson trade.
</P>
<P>
Williams, 32, played 25 games last season as he completed a
remarkable comeback from nerve damage in his left foot. He had
played just 10 games over the previous three campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Williams was a member of the 1989 Detroit Piston, who won the
NBA title. He also played for Phoenix, Charlotte and Indiana and
holds the all-time record with 97 consecutive free throws over
two seasons in 1993. He has career averages of 11.0 points and
5.8 assists in 411 games. 
</P>
