<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The exodus of the
three-time defending champions Chicago Bulls reportedly has begun
as free agent guard Steve Kerr agreed to a multi-year deal with
the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
Kerr, who made the series-winning jumper in the 1997 NBA
Finals against the Utah Jazz, has agreed to undisclosed terms and
will sign the contract on Monday. He made $750,000 last season in
the final year of a four-year contract he signed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Kerr's departure is the first of what is expected to be many
as the Bulls begin an enormous renovation following superstar
Michael Jordan's retirement announcement on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kerr is one of nine free agents from the Bulls, a group that
includes star forward Scottie Pippen and six-time defending re
bound champion Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old Kerr is the all-time leading three-point
shooter and a nice fit for the Spurs, who boast the strong inside
attack of All-Star center David Robinson and Tim Duncan. Despite
the absence of a consistent perimeter shooter, San Antonio won 56
games last season.
</P>
<P>
Kerr averaged 7.5 points last season, his 10th in the NBA and
fifth with Chicago. His career three-point percentage of 0.473 is
best among those with at least 250 made. He won the Long Distance
Shootout at All-Star Weekend in 1997 and his 1994-95 clip of 52.4
percent is an NBA record. 
</P>
