<HEADLINE> Exports of Machinery and Electrical Goods Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua)-- Despite a sluggish export
situation, China exported 66.54 billion U.S. dollars of machinery
and electrical goods last year, a 12.2 percent rise on a yearly
basis, according to a report in the Economic Daily.
</P>
<P>
This figure was higher than the 65 billion-U.S-dollars target
set by the State Council at the beginning of the year, the Daily
said.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted customs statistics showing that in 1998,
China's combined imports and exports of machinery and electrical
goods totaled 130.41 billion U.S. dollars, a growth of 9.9
percent over 1997, and accounted for 40.3 percent of the
country's gross foreign trade volume.
</P>
<P>
The export structure has been further improved, helping bring
about a marked rise in the export of high value-added goods such
as digital processing equipment and high-grade home appliances.
</P>
<P>
The market has also been further diversified, bringing more
trade with North America, the European Union and Africa.
</P>
<P>
The export target set for 1999 is 71.5 billion U.S. dollars,
which would represent a rise of 7.5 percent over last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
