<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gloomy Prospects for Sri Lanka's Export in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Exporters
Association (SLEA) has predicted that 1999 will be an extremely
bad year for the country's export performance, due to drastic
increases in freight rates and severe price competition.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's export growth from January to November last year
had dropped to 3 percent from 14 percent in the previous year,
said sources with the SLEA Monday.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the apparel sector and the agricultural sector all
other exports had declined steeply, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the situation is likely to get worse with
increased freight rates and terminal handling charges as a result
of shipping lines establishing cartels.
</P>
<P>
From January 1999 Terminal Handling Charges have increased by
40 percent to the United States and 55 percent to Europe. Freight
rates have been increased to a further 1000 U.S. dollars per 40
feet container and 600 dollars per 20 feet container.
</P>
<P>
The sources expressed fear of the impending decline and
probable closure threatening the export industry.
</P>
<P>
They said due to devaluation manufacturers from Southeast Asia
have reduced the selling prices of their products and Sri Lanka
has also been compelled to do so.
</P>
<P>
The value of all coconut products have declined from 7,900
million rupees (116 million U.S. dollars) during January-October
1997 to 6,700 million rupees (98.5 million dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Tea prices have taken a downturn since August 1998, which are
expected to continue to fall in 1999, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The prices offered by buyers to the apparel industry has
dropped by 10 percent, said the sources, adding that the rubber
industry has also had to cut down prices to meet international
competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
