<HEADLINE> Cuban, Colombian, Venezuelan Leaders on Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Cuban leader Fidel Castro,
Colombian President Andres Pastrana and Venezuelan
President-elect Hugo Chavez held an informal summit here Sunday
to discuss how to end the decades-long rebel war ravaging
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana briefed the meeting about the ongoing peace process
in Colombia, and Castro and Chavez expressed their support for "a
lasting and stable peace," said a brief joint communique issued
after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders also vowed to promote economic cooperation
and the integration of the Latin American and Caribbean region.
</P>
<P>
The forthcoming series of summits of the Association of
Caribbean States in Dominica in April, between the European Union
(EU) and Latin America and Caribbean states in Brazil in August,
and the Iberian American countries in Cuba by the end of the
year, will play important roles in the process of the
integration, said the three leaders.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the impact of Brazil's recent financial
turmoil on Latin America and trans-national crackdown on
drug-traffiking.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana began his state visit to Cuba on January 14. During
the visit, the two countries signed seven agreements to boost
bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Chavez, who will take office on February 2, joined the summit o
n January 16 after his visit to Europe and Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
