<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Research on Genes of South China Tigers Faces Financial, Technical Difficulties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese research program on
the genes of south China tigers has been suspended for financial
and technical reasons, according to an official in charge of the
program.
</P>
<P>
Cui Liping, director of the China South China Tiger Protection
and Coordination Committee, expressed her hope that both domestic
and overseas research organizations will join the efforts to
promote this research.
</P>
<P>
China created a genetic data base for south China tigers in
Shanghai in 1995 as part of efforts to save this endangered rare
animal species, and the Shanghai Zoo has collected the sperm,
blood, hair and skins of more than 20 South China tigers.
</P>
<P>
Cui said that researches on artificial insemination, external
fertilization, embryo transfer and cloning have not been started
because of insufficient funds, poor research facilities and an
insufficient technical faculty, and the collected samples are now
being kept in canned liquefied nitrogen at 196 degrees below zero
Celsius.
</P>
<P>
Cui said that China now has 51 South China tigers in
captivity, but most of them are close blood relations. Experts
have predicted that these tigers could vanish within 50 years or
two generations unless something is done right now.
</P>
<P>
Cui said the Shanghai Zoo plans to send some blood samples to
the Giant Panda Research Center in Chengdu for DNA analysis to
clarify the blood relationships among the tigers now in
captivity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
