<HEADLINE> Freeway Pileup Injures at Least 12 in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- At least 12 people were
injured as some 50 cars and trucks smashed together in a massive
freeway pileup in Michigan State of the United States on Sunday,
reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The chain-reaction crash occurred on Interstate 94 just south
of Detroit, and the accident was blamed on black ice, fog and
high speed.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Michigan State Police Trooper John Sosa as
saying that the fog and drivers moving too fast "coupled with the
black ice on the roadway caused cars to spin out of control."
</P>
<P>
"Those factors spelled nothing but trouble," he said.
</P>
<P>
The crash led to the closure of the freeway in both directions
over a section of several kilometers for hours. Authorities
reopened I-94 to eastbound traffic at about noon Sunday, two
hours before the westbound lanes were reopened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
