<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State Farms Expected to Grow Six Percent in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China's state farms, key
players in the country's agricultural sector, are expected to
grow by six percent and produce 17.2 million tons of grain this
year, says today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The country's 2,100 state farms now produce a sizable portion
of the total agricultural output, including one-tenth of
state-procured commodity grains and 80 percent of the country's
rubber, according to the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Yuzhuang, director of the ministry's Bureau of State
Farms, said last year's gross national product in the sector grew
by five percent to 43.73 billion yuan (dlrs 5.27 billion), and
grain output hit 16.4 million tons, the second highest harvest in
history.
</P>
<P>
"Central tasks this year are to improve the quality of farm
produce and readjust the product mix to meet diversified market
demands," Zheng said, adding that major products that need
improvement include spring wheat, cotton, fodder corn, sugar
beets and rye.
</P>
<P>
Vice minister of Agriculture Lu Ming has recently told a
national agricultural conference in Beijing that annual growth
rate of state farms has dropped from 9.5 percent in the 1978-96
period to an average 5.7 percent since 1997, and that the
money-losing trend lingers.
</P>
<P>
Lu attributed the downturn to the shrinking markets and export
volume, and urged the state farm sector to apply high technology
to processing of agricultural product as well as the marketing of
farm produce.
</P>
<P>
Enhanced industrialization is expected to allow optimization
of industrial resources and make it more adaptive to the market
economy, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
State farms cover 4.8 million hectares of arable land, about
4.6 percent of the country's total. Since much of them lie in
arid regions, the promotion of applied farming technologies,
especially water-saving irrigation techniques, has a significant
bearing on the farms, experts say.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
