<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Foggy Days in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The number of foggy days in
Beijing has been increasing in recent years due to the
interaction of suspended particles and vapor, environmental
protection experts were quoted as saying by today's Beijing
Morning Post.
</P>
<P>
They backed up their conclusion with statistics showing that
the city's annual foggy days had increased to 256 in 1997, from
only 40 days in 1983, and the number of such days further
increased last year.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that visibility in Beijing was 18 kilometers on
average in the 1950s, but is now less than 10 kilometers. They
explained that solar radiation weakened by heavy suspended
particles in the air has also caused more of moisture in the air.
</P>
<P>
The paper reported that the present-day fog can only be
dispelled by heavy winds because of the huge proportion of
suspended particles in the air. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka-Belgium Trade Grows over Last 10 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's trade with Belgium
has grown during the past ten years, with the balance of trade
being in favor of Sri Lanka, the official Daily News reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"About 30 Belgian companies are involved in investment projects
in Sri Lanka, of which ten are in the diamond cutting and
polishing sector," said a Foreign Ministry's press release on
Minister Lakshman Kadirgamar's recent visit to Belgium.
</P>
<P>
During his trip on January 14 and 15, Mr. Kadirgamar met Herman
Van Rompuy, vice prime minister and minister of budget of Belgium,
for discussions on bilateral relations, said the release.
</P>
<P>
The release said Mr. Kadirgamar briefed the Belgian vice prime
minister on Sri Lanka's continued efforts for economic
liberalization and financial reforms.
</P>
<P>
It was agreed that the two countries would work towards Sri
Lanka receiving an investment mission form Belgium shortly, said
the release.
</P>
<P>
With Brussels being the headquarters of the European Union (EU)
and Sri Lanka chairing the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC), closer relations between the EU and SAARC
were also discussed.
</P>
<P>
These included modalities to develop SAARC access to the Single
European Market; the extension of the Generalized System of
Preferences (GSP) for SAARC products with accumulation of regional
content; cooperation on standards, agriculture, health and related
issues and matters relating to banking and finance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
