<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangxi Consolidates Yangtze Embankment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The east Chinese city of
Jiujiang, which was severely hit by last summer's floods, has
vowed great efforts to reinforce its Yangtze River embankment.
</P>
<P>
A plan mapped out by the local government calls for a total
investment of 1.95 billion yuan to consolidate the
196-kilometer-long embankment at the Jiujiang section of the
Yangtze in Jiangxi Province, and work on this project is now
underway.
</P>
<P>
The renovation will be completed in three years, and when
complete the embankment will be able to withstand water levels
equivalent to the highest flood level in history, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project will consolidate 32.7
kilometers of dikes and dams, involving an investment of 490
million yuan, they added.
</P>
<P>
Nine construction enterprises with sound reputations,
including Gezhouba Water Control, the Electricity Engineering
Group and the Eighth Bureau of the China Water Control and Power
Engineering Company won the bidding for the project, with more
than 80 enterprises competing for the job. The builders have
pledged work of the highest quality.
</P>
<P>
Repair of a breach in the dike has begun and will be completed
by the end of April.  
</P>
</TEXT>
