<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Money Laundering Law Takes Effect in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, January 17 (Xinhua) -- An anti-money laundering
law, the first of its kind in Romania, took effect on Sunday for
the crackdown of rampant under-world economy, which amounts to 22
percent of the country's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Exchange and transfer of money made through illegal deals such
as drug trafficking, smuggling, theft, fraud and tax evasion are
listed as money laundering in the law.
</P>
<P>
Offenders of the law will be jailed for three to 12 years, and
masterminds and accessories for five to 15 years, under the law.
</P>
<P>
A national bureau and provincial branches will be set up for
gathering and analyzing information related to suspected
money-laundering and sending it to judicial departments.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, for sums over 10,000 ECU (about 11,740 U.S.
dollars), the banks and other financial institutions must verify
the client's identity before a transfer is made.
</P>
<P>
Romania annually loses at least one billion U.S. dollars of
revenue because of the under-world economy, which has nearly
doubled in the past five years, according to a survey by an
authoritative institution released in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
