<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Tomb with Anti-robbery Gears Found Robbed in Xi'an </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The builders of a Han Dynasty
(206 B.C. -- 220 A.D.) tomb filled it with sand in order to allow
the dead rest in peace. But their effort has proved futile as
archeologists in Xi'an recently found that this tomb had been rob
bed.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Shaanxi Provincial Archeological Research
Office unearthed the tomb on a building site of the Xi'an
Communications School in the city's northern suburb. The sex of
the tomb's occupant could not be determined because the burial
site was left in a poor condition after it was pilfered.
</P>
<P>
Sand-filled tombs are rare, and this was the first found in
Xi'an. Such tombs are not easily robbed because would-be thieves
are afraid of being inundated by the falling sand, experts said,
adding that these cunning robbers had kept clear of the tomb room
and dug to the bottom, drilling a hole and taking out the buried
treasures.
</P>
<P>
A lamp made in the Song Dynasty (960 A.D. -- 1279 A.D.), which
was left inside the tomb, is an indication that the robbers were
probably Song people.
</P>
<P>
There were more than 50 articles inside the tomb, including
six servants and a number of jars, pots and clocks, reflecting
the high standard of sculpture in that dynasty. However, gold,
silver, and jade articles that were probably placed beside the
noble tomb occupant are missing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
