<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education Priority Given to Ethnic Minorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China will give priority to
ethnic minority groups, particularly the less populous ones while
running to meet its deadline regarding compulsory education,
today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The paper quotes Wang Fulin, spokesman of the State Ethnic
Affairs Commission as saying that the program, kicked off in 1996
to help the students of 22 ethnic minorities, will keep its
momentum this year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 2000, the minorities with a population less than
100,000 people are expected to make high school a must for 85
percent of their students, said Lan Zhiqi, an official with the
education department of the State Ethnic Affairs Commission.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has vowed to make the nine-year
compulsory education program accessible to 85 percent of students
by the end of the century. The task is especially challenging in
ethnic regions, Lan said.
</P>
<P>
Of the country's 55 ethnic minorities, 525,860 people belong
to the 22 groups which have a population of less than 100,000 p
eople, accounting for 0.6 percent of the total minority
population.
</P>
<P>
Most of these small minorities live near borders, where
traditional ways of life are centered around fishing and hunting
in addition to farming. Poverty is still haunting many ethnic r
egions, which hinders the development of education, Lan said.
</P>
<P>
The central government has decided to increase investment in
these areas. Primary school teachers will go through special
training, and high school teacher are to be trained at the
prefecture level. Teachers have to speak both standard Chinese
and the local language, both of which are taught in the schools,
says the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
