<HEADLINE> Crime Cases Hit Six-Year High in Czech Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Public order in the Czech
Republic is worsening, with 426,000 criminal cases registered
last year, hitting a six-year high, police authorities said.
</P>
<P>
Criminal cases have nearly doubled since the country's
transition in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Last year, violence and murder also increased, causing 313
deaths.
</P>
<P>
Direct economic loss resulting from crime in the year amounted
to 33.5 billion koruna (1.12 billion U.S. dollars), with about
two thirds caused by economic crime.
</P>
<P>
The local sources pointed out that lack of severe punishment
and the abolition of death sentence are the main reasons for the
deterioration of social order.
</P>
<P>
A recent poll showed that the majority of the people are in
favor of restoration of capital punishment as a deterrent to
criminals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
