<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Frenchmen Kaphael Poiree Wins World Cup Pursuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Raphael Poiree of France kept a
steady hand on the shooting range to win his third biathlon World
Cup victory of the season when he won a 12.5-kilometer pursuit
event in Ruhpolding, Germany, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Poiree finished the distance in 35 minutes, 21.6 seconds to
beat two German rivals, Ricco Gross and Sven Fischer, who
extended his overall World Cup lead.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchman shot without a fault, while Gross missed one
target and Fischer two. Gross finished 6.5 seconds behind, while
Fischer was 23.7 behind Poiree.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Ole Einar Bjoerndalen of Norway, who finished
a distant 37th in Saturday's sprint, the first leg of the
pursuit, jumped to eighth place.
</P>
<P>
Fischer leads the season standings with 221 points, while his
brother-in-law, Frank Luck, has 208.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 10k pursuit, Olena Zubrilova of Ukraine
continued her domination from Saturday's sprint to win by 5.1
seconds over Corinne Niogret of France. Zubrilova clocked 30:03.5
and overcame two penalty laps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
