<HEADLINE> Rural Economy Contributes Greatly to Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 18 (Xinhua) -- The rural areas around
Shanghai, China's largest industrial city, produced 112 billion
yuan in gross domestic product last year, one-third of the city's
total.
</P>
<P>
According to recent figures from the municipal statistics
bureau, the rural economy grew by 15.2 percent last year and
played a major role in helping the city achieve a 10.1 percent
growth despite the negative impact of the lingering Asian
financial crisis and weakened consumer demand.
</P>
<P>
Deputy mayor Feng Guoqin attributes this development mainly to
the diversified rural economy.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Shanghai's rural areas have stepped up
efforts to draw investment from other parts of the city, and this
has resulted in an increasing number of township enterprises.
Last year, these enterprises reported 270 billion yuan in
industrial output.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors have rushed in to set up 9,280 ventures
over the years, with contractual capital of 15.99 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses have also flourished, especially in several
newly established private economic zones, which turned out 18
billion yuan of industrial output last year, accounting for about
seven percent of all rural output.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
