<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Southernmost Puts Emphasis on Ethnic Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China's southernmost island
province of Hainan is witnessing a leveling out of educational
standards between its ethnic minority group and the Han majority
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic minority people account for 17 percent of the p
rovince's total, but they have received more educational funds
and infrastructure investment than the Han residents over the
past decade, with the annual education appropriation amounting to
300 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Fu Honghe, head of the provincial education department, said
that Hainan has set up a complete educational framework in areas
densely populated by ethnic people, where some 64 percent of the
population have received nine-year compulsory education.
</P>
<P>
There are over 200 middle schools and eight vocational
training schools as well as two adult higher-learning institutes
and a university in the nine ethnic autonomous prefectures.
</P>
<P>
These areas have managed to eliminate illiteracy and the
number of ethnic university students per 10,000 people has incre
ased to 6.5 percent from 3.6 percent in 1990, which is 2.9
percentage points higher than the average level in the province.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there has been a large number of talented graduates
from the area's 20 training schools and secondary schools who have
 helped boost the professional expertise in sectors ranging from
tourism to electronics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
