<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Finds Urban Residents Concerned about Progress of Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- China's urban residents have
voiced their most anxious concerns in a recent survey which finds
that anti-corruption campaign, employment reform and making
changes to the social insurance system are among the top three.
</P>
<P>
The other three issues of most concern include environmental
protection, reform of state-owned enterprises and the
strengthening of the legal system.
</P>
<P>
The survey has polled 785 people in Beijing, Tianjin,
Guangzhou, Chongqing and other large cities.
</P>
<P>
It also indicates that after six consecutive interest rate
cuts by China's Central Bank, savings are now regarded as the
safest and best choice for investments forms by urban residents.
</P>
<P>
Among those surveyed,76.9 percent say that they prefer
saving money in banks and 63.5 percent say they will increase
their deposits, while 23.6 percent say they would choose to buy
securities and stocks.
</P>
<P>
Most of them do not plan to increase their investments in
1999, however, as housing costs are high for most of them and
they would rather wait and see how the economy progresses before
making further decisions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
