<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man-made Rainfall Alleviates Drought in the Yellow River Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Man-made rain has helped
alleviate drought and increase agriculture production on the
upper reaches of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the amount of artificial rainfall has
reached more than three billion cubic meters in the area over the
past two years. The period artificial rainfall lasted more than
180 days and reached 2.07 billion cubic meters in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Yellow River, second longest in China, originates from
Qinghai and passes through nine provinces and autonomous regions,
with a total length of 5,464 kilometers. Since 1990, sustained
drought has caused a sharp decrease of water flow on the upper
reaches, making some river sections dry up on the lower reaches,
affecting the economic expansion of the river valley.
</P>
<P>
High elevation and large pieces of marshland are ideal for
producing rainfall on the upper reaches of the Yellow River,
meteorologists say.
</P>
<P>
Qinghai will step up even greater efforts in producing
rainfall with support from the central government in the next few
years, officials have revealed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
