<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Auto Sales Drops 83 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Domestic Automobile sales in
Indonesia dropped 83 percent in 1998, according to the latest
report from the Association of Indonesian Automotive Industries.
</P>
<P>
A total of 68,413 vehicles were sold at the domestic market.
Sales for 1997 were 392,203 units, local newspapers Monday quoted
the association as saying.
</P>
<P>
December ranked the worst sales month of 1998 with 1,813 units
moving from showrooms, down from 2,394 in November.
</P>
<P>
The best sales month was January, with 14,339 vehicles sold.
</P>
<P>
The country's largest automaker, PT. Astra International,
topped the sales list, selling 31,579 vehicles last year, 45
percent of total sales.
</P>
<P>
There were few buyers for luxury vehicles. In January, only two
Mercedes-Benz vehicles were sold, but the number picked up to 63
in February. The number accounted for a chunk of the total of 444
last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, motorcycle sales fell to 430,948 last year from over
1.8 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is languishing in its worst economic crisis in three
decades, with the rupiah (national currency) losing more than 65
percent of its value against the U.S. dollar from its value in
July 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
