<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Indonesia Issues New Policy on Trade Financing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia (BI) has issued
a new policy extending the government-sponsored trade financing
scheme to all exporters and applicable to the import of all
commodities, the Indonesian Observer reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The new policy was issued on January 11, 1999 and therefore,
exporters can start to utilize the facility or to open the
guaranteed letter of credit through designated banks, BI's Foreign
Affairs Division Chairman Nana Supriatna said.
</P>
<P>
"The new policy is designed to enhance the utilization of the
facility as it has not been used optimally," Nana was quoted by
the paper as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that importers are also eligible for the facility, not
confined to only those holding PET (facilities for certain
exporting companies).
</P>
<P>
"Importers/exporters who do not hold the PET will also be
allowed to utilize the facility," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nana explained that exporters are now allowed to import all
sorts of commodities, not only 46 kinds of commodities as in the
previous ruling, provided that they are raw materials intended for
export-oriented products.
</P>
<P>
"The policy also allows all banks, not only 28 designated
banks, to handle the trade financing on the condition that they
have no arrears in international trade," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nana said that the policy is only applicable to the BI trade
financing scheme, the funds of which is derived from the
government. While, the trade financing scheme provided by other
countries such as Japan Exim Bank and U.S. Exim Bank, are exempted
from the policy.
</P>
<P>
Data at BI shows that the realized trade financing scheme
offered by BI only reached 664 million U.S. dollars of the
allocated 1.2 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
