<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Klinsmann Hangs up His Boots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Former German captain Juergen
Klinsmann has decided not to resume his career in the United
States and has retired for good.
</P>
<P>
"I toyed with the idea and I collected information about Major
League Soccer. But I've decided to retire for good," Klinsmann
told the German sports news agency SID on Sunday from his Los
Angeles home.
</P>
<P>
Klinsmann, 34, retired from the German national team after its
ouster by Croatia in the World Cup quarterfinals in France last
summer.
</P>
<P>
Klinsmann's wife is American and the couple and their son now
live in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
One of the top forwards in the world in the past decade,
Klinsmann, finished his 11-year international career with 108
caps and 47 goals -- sharing second place on the all-time German
scoring list with Rudi Voeller. Gerd Mueller had 68 goals in 62
games.
</P>
<P>
Klinsmann has been without a club contract since leading
Tottenham Hotspur out of the relegation zone in England's Premier
League last season.
</P>
<P>
Klinsmann said he wanted to stage a charity match in Germany
that would also serve as his official farewell.
</P>
<P>
"I really wanted to say good-bye to my fans in Germany. But
the German federation refused to do it. I am very sad and
bitterly disappointed," Klinsmann told SID.
</P>
<P>
The German Soccer Federation (DFB) has stopped staging such
matches for its long-serving players as a matter of principle.
</P>
<P>
Klinsmann said he was not sure now whether he would travel to
Florida for a farewell party when the German team goes there for
matches against the United States on Feb. 6 in Jacksonville and
Colombia on Feb. 9 in Miami. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
