<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Ruling Golkar Apologizes for Past Mistakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian ruling Golkar
(Functional Group) finally apologized to the people for its past
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
"Golkar sincerely apologizes to the entire nation for all
mistakes and wrongdoings of the past," Golkar's General Chairman
Akbar Tandjung said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Akbar said the party also apologized for failing to accommodate
all aspirations of the people during its rule.
</P>
<P>
The apology was the first ever made by the Golkar chairman. The
ruling group came under strong criticism when it said last year it
would not apologize to the public as demanded.
</P>
<P>
Golkar believes that this apology is timely considering the
predominantly Muslim nation will be overwhelmed by the spirit of
Idul Fitri (feast celebrating the end of fasting period) -- that
is, forgiveness, Akbar said.
</P>
<P>
The largest Muslim country in the world, Indonesia, is set to
celebrate the Idul Fitri festivities on January 19 and 20.
</P>
<P>
Golkar has been blamed for many shortcomings considered to have
caused the protracted economic crisis following the downfall of
Soeharto as the president of the New Order government on May 21
last year.
</P>
<P>
Top Golkar executive Marzuki Darusman had apologized to the
people in November last year. However, Akbar said Marzuki's
apology was too early and was thus considered personal, and did
not represent the party as a whole.
</P>
<P>
"At last, golkar's board of executives utilized the momentum
behind this period, and we as an institution, consider it to be a
perfect time to formally apologize to the people for past
mistakes," Akbar was quoted by national newspapers Monday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
During Soeharto's 32-year reign, Golkar always enjoyed
landslide victories in elections. Critics say elections under
Soeharto were identical to money politics and contained an
abundance of vote-rigging.
</P>
<P>
Responding to critics, Akbar said: "What happened in the past
as well as what happens now, are the products of all of us as a
nation, and this includes any socio-political issues. Golkar
admits that shortcomings did exist, and that wrongdoings had taken
place. But, what's more important is the future. Based on a new
commitment, we also vow to look toward a brighter future."
</P>
<P>
He said Golkar is set to enter a new era, an era of openness
and democracy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
