<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Boosts Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, January 18 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province
plans to give priority to tourism this year to make it a pillar
of it's economy.
</P>
<P>
Shandong will adopt a series of preferential policies to
boost the growth of tourism, including investing more in tourist
infrastructure, attracting overseas investment in local tourism
and providing preferential treatment to local tourist businesses
in issuing bonds and stocks.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Shandong received nearly 55 million domestic
tourists and 600,000 overseas tourists, bringing an income of
24.6 billion yuan which accounted for 3.33 percent of it's GDP.
</P>
<P>
In a recent national work conference for tourism, Shandong's
port city of Yantai was credited as one of the first group of
excellent tourist cities in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
