The Australian:
</P>
<P>
-- Two Liberal ministers clashed Sunday over the merits of the
monarchy, amid signs that republican supporters in the Liberal
Party were losing heart. Environment Minister Robert Hill
disagreed with his ministerial colleagues, saying he was firmly
convinced it was time for a change for republic and he would do
whatever he could to help achieve it.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald:
</P>
<P>
-- Parliamentary and public debate about a new preamble to the
constitution of an Australian republic will begin next month
following the release of a report by the Constitutional Centenary
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The Age:
</P>
<P>
-- The Howard Government, upset by UNESCO's plan to place
Kakadu National Park on the world heritage "in danger" list, has
accused the world's environmental watchdog of bias of formulating
an "ideological campaign" against Australia's plan to push ahead
with mining in the park.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review:
</P>
<P>
-- BHP, Australia's biggest mining company, has predicted world
coal prices will fall for at least the next seven years in a
post-Asian crisis market characterized by serious oversupply and
weak demand. 
