<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, January 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Palestinians have agreed to hold a meeting
among the Palestinians, Israel and the United States in
Washington next month to bring the peace talks with Israel back
on track, a senior Palestinian official said on Sunday
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat
as saying the meeting was proposed by the U.S. Middle East Peace
Envoy Dennis Ross last week during his visit in the region.
</P>
<P>
Ross invited chief negotiators from Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority to meet with him in Washington in
early February. (Israel-Palestine)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON-- Brazil's top financial officials met Sunday with
U.S. officials, seeking ways to keep Latin America's largest
economy from succumbing to an Asian-style currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Finance Minister Pedro Malan and central bank
president Francisco Lopes met U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers.
</P>
<P>
The two Brazilian officials also met officials at the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank on Saturday
and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Officials described the talks as a wide-ranging review of
steps Brazil already has taken and what needs to be done to calm
investor unease. (US-Brazil-Crisis )
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON-- The United States urged the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) on Sunday to take a hard look at
military options as a fragile cease-fire unraveled in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to do all that we can do to preserve the
cease-fire," State Department spokesman James Rubin said as NATO
ambassadors prepared to take up the latest crisis in an emergency
session in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The White House held a second day of strategy meetings, and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright called allied leaders to
discuss bloody developments in the Serb province. (US-Kosovo-NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Eighteen people were killed Saturday in a fighting
between Ethiopian government troops and the rebel Oromo
Liberation Front (OLF) militiamen at the Kenyan frontier town of
Moyale in North Eastern Province.
</P>
<P>
Moyale District Commissioner Stephen Kipkabut Sunday
confirmed the incident, saying that the fighting claimed the
lives of 14 Ethiopian soldiers and four OLF militiamen.
</P>
<P>
Kipkabut said that the Ethiopian government forces had
wrongfully crossed the border on the pretext of looking for OLF
militiamen who had attacked their bases.(Kenya-Ethiopia-Clashes)
</P>
</TEXT>
