<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fowler Close to Liverpool Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Robbie Fowler is on the brink
of agreeing a new contract to stay at Liverpool for five years
after his current deal ends in June 2000.
</P>
<P>
Manager Gerard Houllier witnessed Fowler's tremendous
hat-trick in the seven goal mauling of Southampton - when the
Liverpool star completed a century of Premiership goals - and
predicted the imminent end to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
A smiling Houllier claimed: "It won't be long now. Yes, I am
confident.
</P>
<P>
"I expect to know much more by the end of the week. Am I
expecting a positive outcome? Yes, of course I am," he added.
</P>
<P>
Fowler's advisors were at Anfield on Saturday as the player
returned to almost his best form after a near year-long battle to
recover from a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
The belief now at the club, and particularly from Houllier, is
that Fowler wants to stay.
</P>
<P>
Certainly after his outstanding form against the sorry Saints,
he showed his sharpness is almost spot on.
</P>
<P>
He has suffered somewhat this season from probably coming back
too soon from a serious injury, and his battle for true match
sharpness has gone hand in hand with protracted negotiations
about his future.
</P>
<P>
Now he has taken his tally to 13 in 24 games for the season.
The second goal of his hat-trick cracked the century mark, and
he's now got 101 in 175 league matches.
</P>
<P>
His overall goals record for the club is an astonishing 142 in
240 - no wonder Houllier wants to tie him down for a very long
time.
</P>
<P>
The partnership with Michael Owen has totalled 30 already for
the season, and Liverpool are now second only to Manchester
United -- next week's FA Cup opponents at Old Trafford -- in the
Premiership scoring stakes.
</P>
<P>
Liverpool's improved form on the back of a six-match unbeaten
run has given them a genuine chance of finishing in the top three
and taking a Champions League spot, with the FA Cup and at least
a UEFA Cup qualification very much on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Fowler, who is the fourth player after Alan Shearer, Ian
Wright and Les Ferdinand to net a century of Premiership goals, a
dmitted he didn't even realise he had reached the 100 mark.
</P>
<P>
He said: "I didn't realise it was my 100th league goal until
Jamie Carragher ran up to me afterwards to tell me. "He said to
me,that's your 100th goal', and I didn't even know." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
