<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Condemns Kosovo Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- NATO condemned on Sunday the
massacre of 45 Kosovar Albanians after an emergency meeting by its
ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
But the western military alliance did not decide on any
military intervention in the Yugoslav province and called instead
on the Yugoslav authorities to cooperate fully with the
international war crimes tribunal in accordance with the United
Nations resolutions.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement issued late on Sunday, the alliance said
that the urgent meeting demanded the Yugoslav government take
immediate steps to ensure that those responsible for the massacre
that took place last Friday in the village of Racak in southern
Kosovo are brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
"The names of those who participated in the killing and those
who gave the orders must be divulged and they must be handed over
to the international war crimes tribunal for prosecution if
requested," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
NATO also decided to send two of its senior military officers
to the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia next Monday to explain to
the Yugoslav authorities the gravity of the situation and their
obligation to respect all their commitments to NATO and to the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The alliance condemned all acts of violence, the statement
added. "It calls on both sides to cease hostilities immediately
and to begin negotiations toward a lasting political solution
which provides greater autonomy for Kosovo and which preserves the
territorial integrity of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia."
</P>
<P>
The two Belgrade-bound NATO officers are NATO Military
Committee Chairman Klaus Naumann and NATO Supreme Commander in
Europe Wesley Clark.
</P>
<P>
NATO suspended its threat of air strikes against Yugoslavia
late last October but kept the order for strikes in place so that
it could quickly revert to the use of force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Right now a France-led extraction force is being stationed in
nearby Macedonia as a rescue team for the hundreds of
international truce verifiers in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Draft Budget Foresees New Borrowing of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The new German government's draft
budget for 1999 envisages new government borrowing of 33.3 billion
dollars, according to a government sources on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Expenditures are due to increase to 288.76 billion dollars from
270.36 billion dollars the year before as Finance Minister Oskar
Lafontaine refrains from making deep cuts in the social services
sector, reports of the German Press Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Experts, however, expect the Social Democratic-led government
to lower spending in this sector in the year 2000 when the
financial situation is likely to get tighter.
</P>
<P>
Among the "transitory items" were 4.85 billion dollars in cash
transfers to help plug a gaping hole in the postal pension fund
that was far bigger than previously expected as well as transfers
to the state pension fund to finance pension payouts.
</P>
<P>
Revised by this sum, the budget would grow only 1.7 percent to
274.97 billion dollars in 1999, rather than 6.8 per cent, it said.
</P>
<P>
The largest single budget is the 102.54 billion dollars labor
budget, up about 5.92 billion dollars from 1998.
</P>
<P>
The transport and building budget comes second with 28.52
billion dollars followed by the defense budget of 27.98 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet is due to approve the draft budget on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
