<DOCNO> XIE19990118.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 18 Killed in Fighting Between Ethiopian Govt. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen people were killed
Saturday in a fighting between Ethiopian government troops and the
rebel Oromo Liberation Front (OLF) militiamen at the Kenyan
frontier town of Moyale in North Eastern Province.
</P>
<P>
Moyale District Commissioner Stephen Kipkabut Sunday confirmed
the incident, saying that the fighting claimed the lives of 14
Ethiopian soldiers and four OLF militiamen.
</P>
<P>
Kipkabut said that the Ethiopian government forces had
wrongfully crossed the border on the pretext of looking for OLF
militiamen who had attacked their bases.
</P>
<P>
He said that four Kenyans were injured on the Kenyan-Ethiopian
border when the Ethiopian soldiers in pursuit of OLF militiamen,
attacked a village at the Dambalafachala Location of Moyale
District.
</P>
<P>
The injured Kenyans had been identified as two home guards and
two civilians at a Moyale Village which was attacked by the
Ethiopian troops in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Kipkabut said the Ethiopian government forces were engaged in
a shoot- out by a group of armed home guards, injuring two of the
home guards.
</P>
<P>
Following the fighting, many Kenyans were fleeing from the
border areas in fear of fresh escalation of battles, he said.
</P>
<P>
The district commissioner said he had visited the Ethiopian
side Saturday morning after addressing public meetings at
Dambalafachala and its environs to reassure the residents of their
safety with a view to protesting to the Ethiopian authority.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that the Kenyan troops were now patrolling the
border, ready to repulse any other incursions into the Kenyan
side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
